1
00:00:01,685 --> 00:00:09,156
[SPEAKER_18]: Tonight, David Cameron, Ed Miliband and Nick Clegg face our audience here in Leeds Town Hall.

2
00:00:09,237 --> 00:00:11,280
[SPEAKER_18]: This is Question Time.

3
00:00:26,763 --> 00:00:27,304
[SPEAKER_18]: APPLAUSE

4
00:00:27,976 --> 00:00:29,499
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you very much.

5
00:00:29,659 --> 00:00:36,570
[SPEAKER_18]: Over the next 90 minutes, the three party leaders are going to take the stage here and be questioned by our audience, of course, as ever.

6
00:00:36,971 --> 00:00:50,874
[SPEAKER_18]: An audience that tonight is made up of three lots of 25% who intend to vote for each of those three party leaders, and the remaining 25% who are either undecided or supporting other parties.

7
00:00:50,914 --> 00:00:52,296
[SPEAKER_18]: Now, during this programme,

8
00:00:52,276 --> 00:00:54,640
[SPEAKER_18]: As ever on Question Time, you can of course text or tweet.

9
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:56,223
[SPEAKER_18]: Our hashtag is BBC QT.

10
00:00:56,584 --> 00:00:58,187
[SPEAKER_18]: You can follow us at BBC Question Time.

11
00:00:58,227 --> 00:01:00,271
[SPEAKER_18]: You can text comments to 83981.

12
00:01:01,072 --> 00:01:04,338
[SPEAKER_18]: You can push that old red button and see what other people are saying.

13
00:01:04,839 --> 00:01:10,690
[SPEAKER_18]: But let's now get cracking and hear from the leader of the Conservative Party, David Cameron.

14
00:01:23,697 --> 00:01:26,263
[SPEAKER_18]: Our first question comes from Jenny Johnson, please.

15
00:01:26,343 --> 00:01:28,228
[SPEAKER_18]: Jenny Johnson.

16
00:01:28,368 --> 00:01:34,062
[SPEAKER_24]: Were you put to bed with rumours that you plan to cut child tax credit and restrict child benefits to children?

17
00:01:34,632 --> 00:01:36,114
[SPEAKER_19]: Well thank you Jenny for that question.

18
00:01:36,294 --> 00:01:37,636
[SPEAKER_19]: No, I don't want to do that.

19
00:01:37,736 --> 00:01:44,045
[SPEAKER_19]: This report that was out today is something I rejected at the time as Prime Minister and I reject it again today.

20
00:01:44,405 --> 00:01:47,629
[SPEAKER_19]: But I do think it's important we go on reforming welfare.

21
00:01:47,970 --> 00:01:57,923
[SPEAKER_19]: It's worth remembering when I became Prime Minister we had a situation where some families were getting £70,000, £80,000, even £90,000 of housing benefit for one house.

22
00:01:57,903 --> 00:02:05,615
[SPEAKER_19]: And think how many people watching this programme were going out, working hard, paying taxes to keep that family in that house.

23
00:02:05,875 --> 00:02:07,458
[SPEAKER_19]: A house they could never afford to live in.

24
00:02:07,518 --> 00:02:09,461
[SPEAKER_19]: So we've got to go on reforming welfare.

25
00:02:09,721 --> 00:02:11,844
[SPEAKER_19]: Let's make sure that work always pays.

26
00:02:12,185 --> 00:02:17,513
[SPEAKER_19]: And let's go on doing what we've done for the last five years, which is get two million more people back into work.

27
00:02:17,533 --> 00:02:21,379
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the most important thing we can do, helping people off welfare into work.

28
00:02:21,459 --> 00:02:23,522
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the sort of country I want to build the next five years.

29
00:02:27,721 --> 00:02:35,190
[SPEAKER_18]: Sorry, you said you didn't want to put to bed the rumours that you were going to cut child tax credits, you meant you did want to put to bed the rumours?

30
00:02:35,210 --> 00:02:53,931
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes, we have increased child tax credits actually, we increased them by £452 under this government because I was determined that while we had to take difficult decisions, and we have, we were left an absolute nightmare situation to clear up, I wanted to make sure that child poverty continued to fall and it has fallen under this government because of what we did

31
00:02:53,911 --> 00:02:55,759
[SPEAKER_18]: And so that's a guarantee that you won't.

32
00:02:55,779 --> 00:02:56,743
[SPEAKER_18]: Does anybody want to come in on this?

33
00:02:57,125 --> 00:02:58,270
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, you sir, up there at the back.

34
00:02:58,631 --> 00:03:02,166
[SPEAKER_18]: In the middle there.

35
00:03:02,483 --> 00:03:06,588
[SPEAKER_07]: You're quoting £70,000 to £80,000 of benefits.

36
00:03:06,608 --> 00:03:08,310
[SPEAKER_07]: How many families are actually claiming that amount of money?

37
00:03:08,651 --> 00:03:16,521
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, it wasn't a huge number, but the fact is everyone that was, was being paid for by dozens of people going out to work, paying their taxes.

38
00:03:16,861 --> 00:03:28,356
[SPEAKER_19]: Look, if you believe, as I do, we should go on reforming welfare, making sure that work always pays, helping people back into work, and keeping working people's taxes down, that's my programme.

39
00:03:28,336 --> 00:03:35,209
[SPEAKER_19]: If you want unlimited welfare, more increases in welfare and higher taxes for working people, that's Ed Miliband's programme, vote for him.

40
00:03:35,530 --> 00:03:38,155
[SPEAKER_19]: But I say keep reforming welfare, it's the right thing to do.

41
00:03:38,235 --> 00:03:38,556
[SPEAKER_30]: You sir.

42
00:03:39,077 --> 00:03:47,172
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm sorry but I just think you're either deceiving the British public or you know exactly what you're going to do but you're refusing to give specifics.

43
00:03:47,152 --> 00:03:52,661
[SPEAKER_19]: and I find that very, very difficult to understand.

44
00:03:52,681 --> 00:03:54,404
[SPEAKER_19]: And how can I possibly vote for you on that basis?

45
00:03:54,584 --> 00:03:55,946
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, let me answer that very directly.

46
00:03:56,287 --> 00:04:03,178
[SPEAKER_19]: In the last Parliament, we saved £20 billion on welfare, and we need to save something like half that in this Parliament.

47
00:04:03,198 --> 00:04:08,687
[SPEAKER_19]: And as I say, if we don't save the money on welfare, and other parties don't seem to want to do that,

48
00:04:08,667 --> 00:04:13,114
[SPEAKER_19]: then they're going to have to make deep cuts in things like the National Health Service, and I don't want to do that.

49
00:04:13,294 --> 00:04:19,724
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm going to increase spending on the National Health Service every year in the next Parliament, just as I did in the last Parliament.

50
00:04:19,924 --> 00:04:21,406
[SPEAKER_19]: But we can reduce welfare.

51
00:04:21,547 --> 00:04:26,414
[SPEAKER_19]: If, for instance, we get another 2 million people back to work, that will cut the welfare bills.

52
00:04:26,734 --> 00:04:29,018
[SPEAKER_19]: Here's another tough choice I think we do need to make.

53
00:04:29,419 --> 00:04:31,722
[SPEAKER_19]: I think we should say to young people in our country

54
00:04:31,702 --> 00:04:40,917
[SPEAKER_19]: The idea that you can leave school and immediately sign on to Jobseekers Allowance, immediately get a flat with housing benefit, I don't think that should be an option anymore.

55
00:04:41,258 --> 00:04:44,783
[SPEAKER_19]: I think what we should do is say to young people, we want you to have a great future.

56
00:04:44,844 --> 00:04:46,386
[SPEAKER_19]: You should be earning or learning.

57
00:04:46,446 --> 00:04:55,100
[SPEAKER_19]: So we'll make available the apprenticeships, make available the university places, make available the training places, but say you can't start your life on benefits.

58
00:04:55,140 --> 00:04:57,304
[SPEAKER_19]: That's not the way we should work in Britain today.

59
00:05:00,170 --> 00:05:14,035
[SPEAKER_25]: That's all very well, but what about those 18 to 21 year olds who don't have a support network, for them who don't have a family to turn to?

60
00:05:14,496 --> 00:05:20,447
[SPEAKER_25]: Isn't that policy for them specifically going to result in more homeless young people on the streets?

61
00:05:20,467 --> 00:05:23,072
[SPEAKER_19]: I think the lady makes a very important point.

62
00:05:25,988 --> 00:05:34,644
[SPEAKER_19]: Anyone who clearly can't stay at home, who has to live independently because of abuse or what have you, we have to make special provision for them and we would.

63
00:05:35,025 --> 00:05:42,900
[SPEAKER_19]: But the situation today, where you can, age 18, leave school, sign on, get a flat, rather than work,

64
00:05:42,880 --> 00:05:44,863
[SPEAKER_19]: or earn and learn at the same time.

65
00:05:45,003 --> 00:05:46,105
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't think that's right.

66
00:05:46,445 --> 00:05:53,516
[SPEAKER_19]: Look, other countries in Europe have almost abolished youth unemployment because they've taken this approach in, say, Germany or in Holland.

67
00:05:53,837 --> 00:05:55,259
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think we should do the same thing.

68
00:05:55,639 --> 00:05:58,664
[SPEAKER_19]: Look, we have created two million jobs in the last five years.

69
00:05:58,984 --> 00:06:00,967
[SPEAKER_19]: Youth unemployment has come plummeting down.

70
00:06:01,108 --> 00:06:11,183
[SPEAKER_19]: If we stick to the economic plan that's working, we can continue to get unemployment down and give young people what I want, which is the opportunity of an apprenticeship or a university place

71
00:06:11,163 --> 00:06:12,565
[SPEAKER_19]: and the chance of a great career.

72
00:06:12,886 --> 00:06:15,511
[SPEAKER_19]: Starting a life on benefits, frankly, is no life at all.

73
00:06:16,272 --> 00:06:27,411
[SPEAKER_18]: David Cameron, can you just come back to the question that the man here asked, that either you don't know what you're going to do, you've specified getting people back to work, or you do know and you're hiding it.

74
00:06:27,431 --> 00:06:32,901
[SPEAKER_18]: You know Dally Alexander today said you'd asked two years ago for a thing which included massive cuts in child benefit.

75
00:06:33,033 --> 00:06:37,279
[SPEAKER_19]: No, these were some proposals that were produced that I rejected then, not least because...

76
00:06:37,559 --> 00:06:38,440
[SPEAKER_19]: But you asked for them.

77
00:06:38,620 --> 00:06:39,441
[SPEAKER_19]: No, I didn't ask for them.

78
00:06:39,461 --> 00:06:41,063
[SPEAKER_19]: They were proposals that were... Where did they come from?

79
00:06:41,124 --> 00:06:45,890
[SPEAKER_19]: In government, people produced... Look, you've got to remember, step back a second, what we inherited.

80
00:06:46,090 --> 00:06:50,135
[SPEAKER_19]: I became Prime Minister at a time when there was no money left.

81
00:06:50,215 --> 00:06:54,201
[SPEAKER_19]: And I bring this with me everywhere, the note that the Treasury Minister left, and it's...

82
00:06:54,621 --> 00:06:55,102
[SPEAKER_19]: There it is.

83
00:06:55,422 --> 00:06:58,266
[SPEAKER_19]: Dear Chief Secretary, I'm afraid there is no money.

84
00:06:58,486 --> 00:07:00,549
[SPEAKER_19]: That is the situation I inherited.

85
00:07:00,629 --> 00:07:02,972
[SPEAKER_19]: So we have had to make difficult decisions.

86
00:07:02,952 --> 00:07:19,392
[SPEAKER_19]: over these last five years and I accept not every one of the decision has been easy for people but the truth is five years on the deficit is halved, two million people are back in work, the economy is growing faster than any major economy in the Western world and I think what this election is about

87
00:07:19,372 --> 00:07:43,617
[SPEAKER_19]: is do we build on that foundation and build a really strong country where you can get a job, you can keep more of your own money to spend as you choose, you get that apprenticeship, we can build houses for people to buy and own, or do we go right back to the start with Ed Miliband potentially propped up by the SNP who want even more borrowing, even more spending, even more debt, all the things that landed us in that mess in the first place.

88
00:07:43,737 --> 00:07:45,919
[SPEAKER_19]: I never want us to go back there again.

89
00:07:51,468 --> 00:07:58,421
[SPEAKER_18]: Clearly there are some people who are worried that you have a plan to cut child credit and tax credits.

90
00:07:58,601 --> 00:08:02,028
[SPEAKER_18]: Are you saying absolutely as a guarantee that you'll never happen?

91
00:08:02,428 --> 00:08:04,713
[SPEAKER_19]: First of all, child tax credit we increased by £450.

92
00:08:04,993 --> 00:08:06,195
[SPEAKER_19]: And it's not going to fall?

93
00:08:06,356 --> 00:08:07,678
[SPEAKER_19]: Not going to fall.

94
00:08:07,698 --> 00:08:08,700
[SPEAKER_19]: Child benefit?

95
00:08:08,680 --> 00:08:11,345
[SPEAKER_19]: to me is one of the most important benefits there is.

96
00:08:11,485 --> 00:08:14,109
[SPEAKER_19]: It goes directly to the family, normally to the mother.

97
00:08:14,129 --> 00:08:16,914
[SPEAKER_19]: £20 for the first child, £14 for the second.

98
00:08:17,034 --> 00:08:20,941
[SPEAKER_19]: It is the key part of families' budgets in this country.

99
00:08:20,961 --> 00:08:22,464
[SPEAKER_19]: Now that's not what we need to change.

100
00:08:22,724 --> 00:08:25,249
[SPEAKER_19]: What we need to change is, again, what did I inherit?

101
00:08:25,649 --> 00:08:26,571
[SPEAKER_19]: A system

102
00:08:26,551 --> 00:08:35,000
[SPEAKER_19]: where if you worked an extra hour or an extra shift, you could sometimes find you actually lost money from that extra hour or that extra shift.

103
00:08:35,020 --> 00:08:42,588
[SPEAKER_19]: So universal credit that we're introducing, coming in now, means every hour you work, you keep more of the money that you earn.

104
00:08:42,628 --> 00:08:44,650
[SPEAKER_19]: And we're going to introduce that right across the country.

105
00:08:44,951 --> 00:08:48,254
[SPEAKER_19]: That will save money and form part of the welfare savings we need to make.

106
00:08:48,294 --> 00:08:49,856
[SPEAKER_18]: Let me bring a couple more people in.

107
00:08:50,297 --> 00:08:51,698
[SPEAKER_18]: The woman there, and then I'll come to you.

108
00:08:51,728 --> 00:09:00,422
[SPEAKER_00]: If things are so fantastic and we've all got more money to spend, why are more families relying on food banks and why are more people and more children in poverty than ever before?

109
00:09:07,169 --> 00:09:09,251
[SPEAKER_19]: I think you ask an absolutely key question.

110
00:09:09,391 --> 00:09:11,133
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm not saying everything is perfect.

111
00:09:11,233 --> 00:09:13,395
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm saying we have not finished the work.

112
00:09:13,976 --> 00:09:24,387
[SPEAKER_19]: That's why I'm so keen to do another five years of continuing to get the country back to work, to build a strong economy, to pay down our debts, and to hand on a really good country to our children.

113
00:09:24,507 --> 00:09:25,968
[SPEAKER_19]: That's what this is all about.

114
00:09:26,029 --> 00:09:27,510
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm not saying we fixed it.

115
00:09:27,570 --> 00:09:31,774
[SPEAKER_19]: It takes a long time to fix the mess that I was left to clear up.

116
00:09:31,814 --> 00:09:35,218
[SPEAKER_19]: But what I would say is we're halfway through a building job.

117
00:09:35,198 --> 00:09:44,706
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, you can keep the team that are building the strong economy or you can go back to the team, frankly, the ones that designed the building that fell down in the first place.

118
00:09:44,827 --> 00:09:45,970
[SPEAKER_19]: I think that would be a terrible mistake.

119
00:09:45,990 --> 00:09:47,796
[SPEAKER_18]: You want to come in and I'll come to you and then we'll go on.

120
00:09:47,976 --> 00:09:48,297
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes.

121
00:09:48,428 --> 00:09:51,432
[SPEAKER_43]: You talk about the sort of country we want to hand on to our children.

122
00:09:51,792 --> 00:09:59,543
[SPEAKER_43]: I don't want to hand on a country to my child where there are a million use in food banks, where people have been hit by really punitive benefit sanctions.

123
00:09:59,603 --> 00:10:03,188
[SPEAKER_43]: People have died, you know, from the bedroom tax.

124
00:10:03,488 --> 00:10:14,062
[SPEAKER_43]: We've got cases where people have a disabled... A woman has had a disabled daughter die and then receive a demand for bedroom tax for the spare room that disabled daughter has left behind.

125
00:10:14,463 --> 00:10:18,368
[SPEAKER_43]: That is not a country I want to hand on to my child.

126
00:10:20,913 --> 00:10:27,142
[SPEAKER_19]: First of all, let me say, I don't want anyone to have to rely on a food bank in our country.

127
00:10:27,162 --> 00:10:30,608
[SPEAKER_19]: It's important that they're there, but I don't want anyone to have to rely on them.

128
00:10:30,628 --> 00:10:36,196
[SPEAKER_19]: The most important thing we can do is to get more people into work.

129
00:10:36,256 --> 00:10:37,858
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the best route out of poverty.

130
00:10:38,199 --> 00:10:42,525
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, two million more jobs is more than the rest of Europe put together.

131
00:10:42,786 --> 00:10:44,288
[SPEAKER_19]: But have we finished the job?

132
00:10:44,268 --> 00:10:45,570
[SPEAKER_19]: Someone said zero-hours contract.

133
00:10:45,850 --> 00:10:48,574
[SPEAKER_19]: One in 50 jobs is a zero-hours contract.

134
00:10:48,975 --> 00:10:51,879
[SPEAKER_19]: Two-thirds of the jobs we've created are full-time jobs.

135
00:10:51,899 --> 00:10:57,688
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, if you're saying the job isn't finished, I absolutely agree, and that is why I'm so passionate about completing the job.

136
00:10:57,708 --> 00:11:00,853
[SPEAKER_19]: And, madam, you asked, what country do you want to pass on to our children?

137
00:11:01,434 --> 00:11:10,427
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't want us to go on borrowing year after year, racking up debts that we then ask our children to pay because we didn't have the courage to pay them off ourselves.

138
00:11:10,407 --> 00:11:16,557
[SPEAKER_19]: And this goes to the heart of the election campaign because Ed Miliband will stand here in a few minutes time.

139
00:11:16,958 --> 00:11:20,123
[SPEAKER_19]: He is saying go on with the budget deficit forever.

140
00:11:20,784 --> 00:11:25,492
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm saying once the economy starts to grow you should be putting money aside for a rainy day.

141
00:11:25,612 --> 00:11:28,677
[SPEAKER_19]: Otherwise we will burden our children with too much debt and that's not right.

142
00:11:29,459 --> 00:11:30,601
[SPEAKER_19]: What was that?

143
00:11:30,621 --> 00:11:35,048
[SPEAKER_09]: Why don't you debate with him directly instead of pointing fingers at him?

144
00:11:40,124 --> 00:11:45,073
[SPEAKER_19]: We debate in the House of Commons 146 times.

145
00:11:45,194 --> 00:11:46,917
[SPEAKER_19]: And I would have voted for you.

146
00:11:46,937 --> 00:11:48,059
[SPEAKER_19]: We debate 146 times in the House of Commons.

147
00:11:48,179 --> 00:11:49,221
[SPEAKER_19]: It's not always that instructive.

148
00:11:49,241 --> 00:11:53,730
[SPEAKER_19]: Actually, I think this is giving you the chance to ask questions directly.

149
00:11:53,870 --> 00:11:56,735
[SPEAKER_19]: I actually think this is more powerful than a television debate.

150
00:11:56,775 --> 00:11:58,238
[SPEAKER_18]: And let's go on to another question.

151
00:11:58,599 --> 00:12:00,262
[SPEAKER_18]: It's a similar subject, really.

152
00:12:00,282 --> 00:12:01,484
[SPEAKER_18]: Lorna Jasper, please.

153
00:12:01,945 --> 00:12:03,027
[SPEAKER_18]: Lorna Jasper.

154
00:12:03,952 --> 00:12:13,000
[SPEAKER_39]: OK. Is needing a law to guarantee your no tax rises promise an acknowledgement that you were in the habit of lying in your pre-election promises?

155
00:12:14,887 --> 00:12:19,975
[SPEAKER_18]: This, of course, is the announcement yesterday that you're going to pass the law.

156
00:12:19,995 --> 00:12:23,079
[SPEAKER_19]: The reason for making this pledge is I really want to be clear with people.

157
00:12:23,540 --> 00:12:25,884
[SPEAKER_19]: Over the last five years, we've made difficult decisions.

158
00:12:25,924 --> 00:12:27,266
[SPEAKER_19]: We've talked about some of that tonight.

159
00:12:27,646 --> 00:12:30,491
[SPEAKER_19]: It hasn't been easy, I know, for many people in Britain.

160
00:12:30,551 --> 00:12:32,213
[SPEAKER_19]: But it's, I think, been the right thing to do.

161
00:12:32,874 --> 00:12:34,417
[SPEAKER_19]: I now know what is in the books.

162
00:12:34,717 --> 00:12:35,859
[SPEAKER_19]: I know what needs to be done.

163
00:12:36,219 --> 00:12:40,025
[SPEAKER_19]: And I know we can finish the job without putting up people's taxes.

164
00:12:40,426 --> 00:12:41,407
[SPEAKER_19]: And my fear is this.

165
00:12:41,427 --> 00:12:42,649
[SPEAKER_19]: Those people

166
00:12:42,629 --> 00:12:52,922
[SPEAKER_19]: who've opposed every step that we've taken, every cut we've had to make, I think they will make a cut of their own, which is to put up taxes to reach into your pay packet and to cut your pay.

167
00:12:53,062 --> 00:12:53,983
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't want to do that.

168
00:12:54,443 --> 00:13:06,358
[SPEAKER_19]: So if you want a government that finds more efficiencies in government spending, that goes on reforming welfare and doesn't put up taxes for working people, indeed cuts taxes for working people, that's me.

169
00:13:06,338 --> 00:13:13,717
[SPEAKER_19]: If you want a government that goes on with unreformed welfare, that doesn't find savings in government spending and puts up taxes, that's the other guy.

170
00:13:13,797 --> 00:13:14,559
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the choice.

171
00:13:14,579 --> 00:13:15,561
[SPEAKER_18]: But why do you need a law?

172
00:13:15,601 --> 00:13:17,647
[SPEAKER_18]: Exactly, the question is why do you need a law?

173
00:13:17,667 --> 00:13:20,714
[SPEAKER_18]: And I would cite to you what your Chancellor said.

174
00:13:20,774 --> 00:13:22,980
[SPEAKER_19]: I want to put it absolutely beyond doubt.

175
00:13:22,960 --> 00:13:30,456
[SPEAKER_19]: I really want hard-working people in our country who work every hour, who want to have a better future for themselves and their families.

176
00:13:30,997 --> 00:13:41,239
[SPEAKER_19]: I want them to know that we're not going to put up VAT or national insurance or income tax because we know we can make the remaining savings without having to attack their wallets.

177
00:13:41,219 --> 00:13:42,723
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the pledge I make.

178
00:13:43,023 --> 00:13:56,155
[SPEAKER_18]: When Alistair Darling tried the same thing, your Chancellor said no other Chancellor in the long history of the office has felt the need to pass a law in order to convince people he has the political will to implement his own budget.

179
00:13:56,195 --> 00:13:58,661
[SPEAKER_18]: Why do you suddenly need to pass a law?

180
00:13:58,681 --> 00:13:59,363
[SPEAKER_19]: Because that was at a

181
00:13:59,343 --> 00:14:01,026
[SPEAKER_18]: Which can be changed anyways, we know.

182
00:14:01,046 --> 00:14:06,317
[SPEAKER_19]: Because that was at a time when the budget deficit was forecast to be bigger than the deficit in Greece.

183
00:14:06,337 --> 00:14:07,239
[SPEAKER_19]: That's what we inherited.

184
00:14:07,560 --> 00:14:10,366
[SPEAKER_19]: So making that sort of promise then was meaningless.

185
00:14:10,526 --> 00:14:15,917
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, having spent five years as Prime Minister, knowing what needs to be done, and let me be clear about...

186
00:14:15,897 --> 00:14:16,959
[SPEAKER_19]: what still needs to be done.

187
00:14:17,079 --> 00:14:22,307
[SPEAKER_19]: We've got to save one out of every £100 the government spends for each of the next two years.

188
00:14:22,668 --> 00:14:24,831
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the extent of the efficiencies that are needed.

189
00:14:25,171 --> 00:14:34,166
[SPEAKER_19]: And then we can start to see public spending growing again to make sure that we go on putting money into our schools and hospitals and all the important public services that we have.

190
00:14:34,186 --> 00:14:34,586
[SPEAKER_19]: We may come back.

191
00:14:34,606 --> 00:14:36,569
[SPEAKER_18]: Laura Jasper, do you want to come back on this question?

192
00:14:37,150 --> 00:14:38,833
[SPEAKER_39]: I more or less was going to say what you said.

193
00:14:39,774 --> 00:14:41,056
[SPEAKER_18]: Oh right, OK.

194
00:14:41,076 --> 00:14:42,158
[SPEAKER_18]: The woman there.

195
00:14:42,138 --> 00:14:44,229
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't want to have you repeating things.

196
00:14:44,249 --> 00:14:49,819
[SPEAKER_22]: You say that you know what needs to be done, so why aren't you announcing where those benefits cuts are coming from?

197
00:14:52,330 --> 00:14:56,797
[SPEAKER_19]: What we're saying, very precisely, is that we need to make another £30 billion of savings.

198
00:14:56,817 --> 00:14:58,540
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the one in £100.

199
00:14:58,801 --> 00:15:03,969
[SPEAKER_19]: So £5 billion of that should come from the tax evaders and the aggressive tax avoiders.

200
00:15:03,989 --> 00:15:05,892
[SPEAKER_19]: We've gone after them every year in government.

201
00:15:06,093 --> 00:15:07,235
[SPEAKER_19]: We'll continue to do that.

202
00:15:07,595 --> 00:15:13,545
[SPEAKER_19]: We then need to go on making savings in government departments through efficiencies, and then the welfare savings that I've talked about.

203
00:15:13,525 --> 00:15:17,032
[SPEAKER_19]: That's my plan, and that gets us to a budget surplus.

204
00:15:17,092 --> 00:15:23,103
[SPEAKER_19]: It means we're paying down the debts, we're passing on a better country to our children, and crucially, we're not putting up taxes.

205
00:15:23,143 --> 00:15:25,227
[SPEAKER_19]: Indeed, I want to cut people's taxes.

206
00:15:26,049 --> 00:15:27,271
[SPEAKER_19]: People talk about the cost of living.

207
00:15:27,572 --> 00:15:31,399
[SPEAKER_19]: The biggest element of the cost of living is the tax you pay at the end of the month.

208
00:15:31,379 --> 00:15:37,426
[SPEAKER_19]: and I say you should be able to earn £12,500 a year before you start paying income tax.

209
00:15:37,446 --> 00:15:42,292
[SPEAKER_19]: That would take people on minimum wage working 30 hours a week out of tax altogether.

210
00:15:42,572 --> 00:15:48,439
[SPEAKER_19]: We should stop taxing poor people in this country in the way that we do today and that's part of our programme for the future.

211
00:15:48,459 --> 00:15:50,241
[SPEAKER_21]: But that wasn't my question, Mr Cameron.

212
00:15:50,261 --> 00:15:53,845
[SPEAKER_18]: Alright, let's have another question from Chair Dear Hoolikin, please.

213
00:15:54,306 --> 00:15:55,227
[SPEAKER_18]: Chair Dear Hoolikin.

214
00:15:56,202 --> 00:15:59,367
[SPEAKER_28]: Why do you think voters don't trust your party with our NHS?

215
00:15:59,427 --> 00:16:01,490
[SPEAKER_18]: It's another question on trust, David Cameron.

216
00:16:01,510 --> 00:16:04,434
[SPEAKER_18]: Why do you think voters don't trust your party with the NHS?

217
00:16:04,735 --> 00:16:07,218
[SPEAKER_19]: All I can say is what I think and what I believe.

218
00:16:07,739 --> 00:16:13,227
[SPEAKER_19]: And when my disabled son was desperately ill, I went to the NHS night after night.

219
00:16:13,528 --> 00:16:14,609
[SPEAKER_19]: I went to different hospitals.

220
00:16:14,689 --> 00:16:15,751
[SPEAKER_19]: I was in different places.

221
00:16:16,072 --> 00:16:20,438
[SPEAKER_19]: But I got the most fantastic care, support, and I'd say love

222
00:16:20,418 --> 00:16:23,064
[SPEAKER_19]: from those people in the NHS for my family and for my son.

223
00:16:23,465 --> 00:16:28,616
[SPEAKER_19]: It was always there for me and I will always make sure it is there for other families in our country.

224
00:16:28,636 --> 00:16:32,726
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, I showed you that note about we had no money when we became the government.

225
00:16:32,746 --> 00:16:38,258
[SPEAKER_19]: When we got that note, we still made a very big decision, which is we said, yes, we're going to have to make cuts

226
00:16:38,238 --> 00:16:43,525
[SPEAKER_19]: in some areas of government spending, but the NHS is going to get more money every year I'm Prime Minister.

227
00:16:43,786 --> 00:16:54,160
[SPEAKER_19]: And it has had more money, and that's why there are, compared with when I became Prime Minister, 9,000 more doctors, there are 7,000 more nurses, we're carrying out millions more operations every year.

228
00:16:54,480 --> 00:16:55,602
[SPEAKER_19]: Do I think it's perfect?

229
00:16:55,962 --> 00:16:57,985
[SPEAKER_19]: No I don't, and I've got a big ambition.

230
00:16:57,965 --> 00:17:07,614
[SPEAKER_19]: for the next five years, which is to deliver a seven-day-a-week NHS, including seven-day opening, eight in the morning, eight in the evening, for GP surgeries.

231
00:17:07,794 --> 00:17:12,238
[SPEAKER_19]: I know we can do that, because we're already delivering it to about eight million people in our country.

232
00:17:12,598 --> 00:17:19,184
[SPEAKER_19]: If you elect me as Prime Minister, I'll finish the job and make sure we have seven-day opening for GP surgeries right across our country.

233
00:17:19,204 --> 00:17:25,710
[SPEAKER_19]: That will really help working people to access the NHS that we all want.

234
00:17:26,686 --> 00:17:33,654
[SPEAKER_18]: Why spend three billion or so on what was described as damaging and distracting reorganisations of the NHS by the King's Fund?

235
00:17:33,674 --> 00:17:46,990
[SPEAKER_19]: The changes we've made actually are saving money in the NHS and because we got rid of 20,000 administrators and bureaucrats in the NHS, that's one of the ways we've been able to fund the extra doctors and the extra nurses.

236
00:17:47,371 --> 00:17:48,272
[SPEAKER_19]: Again,

237
00:17:48,252 --> 00:17:56,209
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't want to hark on about what I inherited, but when I became Prime Minister, the growth in the number of bureaucrats was going up four times as fast as the number of nurses.

238
00:17:56,229 --> 00:17:58,875
[SPEAKER_19]: But I make the point because it's been a recovery job.

239
00:17:58,895 --> 00:17:59,537
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the point.

240
00:17:59,717 --> 00:18:04,708
[SPEAKER_19]: And the NHS is stronger today than it was five years ago.

241
00:18:04,688 --> 00:18:06,170
[SPEAKER_34]: Good evening Mr Cameron.

242
00:18:06,912 --> 00:18:18,832
[SPEAKER_34]: The fact that Jeremy Hunt has promised an extra £8 billion for the health service is very welcome, but surely anybody with half a brain can see that the NHS isn't sustainable in its present form, just pouring more and more money into it.

243
00:18:19,413 --> 00:18:20,394
[SPEAKER_34]: What are your thoughts on that?

244
00:18:20,574 --> 00:18:21,176
[SPEAKER_18]: How do you mean?

245
00:18:21,256 --> 00:18:22,558
[SPEAKER_18]: That it needs more money?

246
00:18:22,578 --> 00:18:24,501
[SPEAKER_34]: Well you can't just keep pouring more and more money.

247
00:18:24,521 --> 00:18:28,688
[SPEAKER_34]: We already put a sixth of GDP into the health service, don't we?

248
00:18:28,668 --> 00:18:30,895
[SPEAKER_34]: You can't keep putting more and more money into it.

249
00:18:30,935 --> 00:18:32,500
[SPEAKER_19]: It's very dangerous in elections to disagree with people.

250
00:18:32,540 --> 00:18:34,145
[SPEAKER_19]: But I don't agree with you, sir.

251
00:18:34,225 --> 00:18:35,348
[SPEAKER_19]: I actually think... Well, you're wrong.

252
00:18:35,449 --> 00:18:40,283
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, OK.

253
00:18:40,303 --> 00:18:40,664
[SPEAKER_19]: I should be there.

254
00:18:40,684 --> 00:18:41,046
[SPEAKER_19]: I should be there.

255
00:18:41,066 --> 00:18:41,226
[SPEAKER_19]: APPLAUSE

256
00:18:42,488 --> 00:18:57,238
[SPEAKER_19]: I think actually if you look at our health system and compare it with others in the world it comes out very strongly on its performance and it also comes out very strongly on how cost effective it is and as we become a wealthier country we should put more money into our NHS so it's always there for us.

257
00:18:57,539 --> 00:18:58,962
[SPEAKER_19]: Look there's a lot we can do

258
00:18:58,942 --> 00:19:28,662
[SPEAKER_19]: to take pressure off the NHS, we've got to do better in terms of public health, we've got to do better in terms of health education, there are all sorts of things about diabetes and smoking and other things where public health issues can really take the pressure off the NHS, but I'm a profound believer that our model is the right one and if as long as I'm Prime Minister it will be free at the point of use, available to all on the basis of need and we will go on putting the money it needs into it, not least because we have taken the difficult decisions elsewhere that

259
00:19:28,642 --> 00:19:29,844
[SPEAKER_19]: some people have been talking back to me.

260
00:19:29,864 --> 00:19:31,287
[SPEAKER_19]: The lady behind me here.

261
00:19:31,367 --> 00:19:32,329
[SPEAKER_36]: Good evening Mr Cameron.

262
00:19:32,349 --> 00:19:32,990
[SPEAKER_36]: Good evening.

263
00:19:33,090 --> 00:19:39,182
[SPEAKER_36]: I'd just like to ask, is it really so difficult to achieve the accident emergency waiting times?

264
00:19:39,643 --> 00:19:41,085
[SPEAKER_36]: Have we found a best way?

265
00:19:41,526 --> 00:19:43,189
[SPEAKER_36]: And what are the actual blockers?

266
00:19:43,249 --> 00:19:50,042
[SPEAKER_36]: Because it just seems that, you know, every week in the media that, you know, we're not hitting these four hour targets, so what are your plans moving forward?

267
00:19:50,022 --> 00:19:51,465
[SPEAKER_19]: I think you make a really good point.

268
00:19:51,966 --> 00:20:03,148
[SPEAKER_19]: Actually that local hospital here does meet the target of seeing 95% of people within four hours and it's important to have that target because we want to know that we're getting the best out of our NHS.

269
00:20:03,509 --> 00:20:10,984
[SPEAKER_19]: The problem we've had recently is just the numbers of frail elderly in our country and the growth of the population of our country has put a lot of pressure on the NHS.

270
00:20:10,964 --> 00:20:21,201
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think my solution of having this seven-day opening for GPs and making sure GP surgeries are easier to access for people, I think that will take pressure off the NHS.

271
00:20:21,541 --> 00:20:32,699
[SPEAKER_19]: I also think making sure social care works together better with the NHS, so we combine the budgets and make sure we help to get elderly people out of hospital, often blocked in beds when they could be looked after at home.

272
00:20:33,080 --> 00:20:35,203
[SPEAKER_19]: Those things, I think, will keep the pressure off.

273
00:20:35,243 --> 00:20:38,068
[SPEAKER_19]: But it's always going to be hard work to make sure we deliver these

274
00:20:38,048 --> 00:20:43,937
[SPEAKER_18]: Just before we leave it, do you have an answer to the question, which is why don't people trust the Conservatives on the NHS?

275
00:20:43,997 --> 00:20:45,419
[SPEAKER_18]: All the polling shows that.

276
00:20:45,439 --> 00:20:47,563
[SPEAKER_19]: I mean, to me, it is my life's work.

277
00:20:47,643 --> 00:20:52,290
[SPEAKER_19]: I profoundly believe that the NHS grows with a Conservative government like what I've been leading.

278
00:20:52,330 --> 00:20:53,151
[SPEAKER_19]: We put the money in.

279
00:20:53,432 --> 00:20:54,613
[SPEAKER_19]: I care about it passionately.

280
00:20:54,954 --> 00:21:00,242
[SPEAKER_19]: And I've got seven days left to prove to people that the NHS, to get... Also, I'd make this point.

281
00:21:00,222 --> 00:21:03,888
[SPEAKER_19]: You only ultimately have a strong NHS if you have a strong economy.

282
00:21:04,129 --> 00:21:06,913
[SPEAKER_19]: We've got that strong economy now, don't put that at risk.

283
00:21:07,735 --> 00:21:08,937
[SPEAKER_19]: You know where they cut the NHS?

284
00:21:09,518 --> 00:21:12,663
[SPEAKER_19]: Portugal, terrible economy, cut the NHS 17%.

285
00:21:13,184 --> 00:21:16,129
[SPEAKER_19]: Greece, catastrophic economy, cut the NHS 13%.

286
00:21:16,790 --> 00:21:22,520
[SPEAKER_19]: It's the economies that tank and bomb where you can't support the health service that our country needs and I think we all deserve.

287
00:21:22,540 --> 00:21:25,285
[SPEAKER_18]: Alright, let's go on.

288
00:21:26,328 --> 00:21:29,176
[SPEAKER_18]: Bob Wilson, a question from Bob Wilson.

289
00:21:29,377 --> 00:21:30,741
[SPEAKER_18]: Sorry to those of you who have your hands up.

290
00:21:30,761 --> 00:21:32,084
[SPEAKER_18]: I can't bring everybody in, obviously.

291
00:21:32,285 --> 00:21:33,147
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, Mr Cameron.

292
00:21:33,609 --> 00:21:39,405
[SPEAKER_03]: I'd like to ask, if we remain in the EU, how will you and how can you control immigration?

293
00:21:39,927 --> 00:21:40,107
[SPEAKER_19]: Right.

294
00:21:40,589 --> 00:21:41,772
[SPEAKER_19]: Very important question, Bob.

295
00:21:43,355 --> 00:21:55,069
[SPEAKER_19]: We can control immigration from outside the EU in the way we do now by closing down these bogus colleges, and we've closed down about 800 of them, and we can do it by having a cap on migration for economic reasons coming into the country.

296
00:21:55,089 --> 00:21:55,890
[SPEAKER_19]: What can you get that done?

297
00:21:55,970 --> 00:21:57,732
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm going to do it inside the EU.

298
00:21:58,092 --> 00:22:01,136
[SPEAKER_19]: The key changes that I'm going to make, if you re-elect me, are these.

299
00:22:01,316 --> 00:22:06,742
[SPEAKER_19]: First of all, anyone coming from an EU country cannot claim unemployment benefit while they're looking for a job.

300
00:22:07,303 --> 00:22:11,708
[SPEAKER_19]: Second, if they're here after six months and haven't got a job, they have to go home.

301
00:22:11,688 --> 00:22:18,639
[SPEAKER_19]: Third, you'd have to work here for four years paying into the system before you get tax credits and other benefits out of the system.

302
00:22:19,019 --> 00:22:25,650
[SPEAKER_19]: And fourth, if you're living here but your family's back at home, you will no longer be able to send the child benefit home to your family.

303
00:22:25,690 --> 00:22:28,274
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, those four changes are big changes.

304
00:22:28,354 --> 00:22:30,898
[SPEAKER_19]: They'll make a real difference and help us to control immigration.

305
00:22:30,918 --> 00:22:33,662
[SPEAKER_19]: And if I'm prime minister, that's what you'll get.

306
00:22:36,342 --> 00:22:40,273
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm sure a lot of people have questions on this, but a couple of points.

307
00:22:40,614 --> 00:22:42,239
[SPEAKER_18]: First of all, we looked at the figures of this.

308
00:22:42,560 --> 00:22:48,396
[SPEAKER_18]: Under 6% of EU nationals living in this country claim benefits of any kind.

309
00:22:48,818 --> 00:22:51,465
[SPEAKER_18]: Under 6%.

310
00:22:51,445 --> 00:22:53,568
[SPEAKER_18]: stopping that is going to hugely reduce the number.

311
00:22:53,608 --> 00:22:56,411
[SPEAKER_18]: And the other thing is... Let me answer that one because that's important.

312
00:22:56,431 --> 00:22:58,514
[SPEAKER_19]: The point I'm saying is it's the in-work benefits.

313
00:22:58,594 --> 00:23:04,281
[SPEAKER_19]: At the moment, someone coming from an EU country is effectively getting around £8,000 to come and work here.

314
00:23:04,702 --> 00:23:06,784
[SPEAKER_19]: Now I'm not saying they shouldn't be able to come and work here.

315
00:23:07,085 --> 00:23:09,868
[SPEAKER_19]: British people can go and work in other European countries.

316
00:23:10,169 --> 00:23:14,915
[SPEAKER_19]: But we do have a benefit system that skews it in favour of people coming to work here.

317
00:23:14,935 --> 00:23:15,996
[SPEAKER_19]: That needs to change.

318
00:23:16,016 --> 00:23:20,001
[SPEAKER_19]: Now that needs change in Europe and so you need a Prime Minister that's prepared to get change

319
00:23:19,981 --> 00:23:20,482
[SPEAKER_19]: in Europe.

320
00:23:20,502 --> 00:23:22,326
[SPEAKER_19]: We may come to Europe.

321
00:23:22,407 --> 00:23:23,229
[SPEAKER_18]: I hope we do.

322
00:23:23,269 --> 00:23:24,632
[SPEAKER_18]: One other thing.

323
00:23:24,712 --> 00:23:30,726
[SPEAKER_18]: How much do you want to get the net migration from outside the EU down to?

324
00:23:31,007 --> 00:23:36,880
[SPEAKER_19]: The combined figure, I want to see net immigration into the EU come down under 100,000.

325
00:23:36,920 --> 00:23:38,985
[SPEAKER_19]: The reason I set that target

326
00:23:38,965 --> 00:23:56,991
[SPEAKER_19]: It's back in the 1990s, we were members of the EU, we had an open and successful economy, but before Labour got in and opened the doors, we did have net migration in the tens of thousands, not the hundreds of thousands, so I believe that's the right ambition.

327
00:23:56,971 --> 00:23:58,934
[SPEAKER_44]: You made similar promises in 2010.

328
00:23:58,954 --> 00:24:00,157
[SPEAKER_44]: You lied.

329
00:24:00,277 --> 00:24:01,118
[SPEAKER_44]: Immigration rules.

330
00:24:01,298 --> 00:24:02,360
[SPEAKER_44]: How can we believe you now?

331
00:24:02,921 --> 00:24:04,224
[SPEAKER_19]: Well let me answer that very directly.

332
00:24:04,484 --> 00:24:08,210
[SPEAKER_19]: I made the promise and outside the EU we did get immigration down.

333
00:24:08,571 --> 00:24:18,388
[SPEAKER_19]: Inside the EU, partly because the rest of the EU's economy has not performed and we've created more jobs than the rest of the EU put together, it's been very difficult to meet that target.

334
00:24:18,368 --> 00:24:24,919
[SPEAKER_19]: I now need to make these benefit changes, these welfare changes, the things I've just described, and I need to negotiate those in Europe.

335
00:24:24,939 --> 00:24:27,343
[SPEAKER_19]: Now I would argue I've got a track record of that.

336
00:24:27,484 --> 00:24:30,689
[SPEAKER_19]: I cut the European budget, first Prime Minister ever to do it.

337
00:24:31,030 --> 00:24:34,335
[SPEAKER_19]: I vetoed a European treaty because it wasn't in our national interest.

338
00:24:34,576 --> 00:24:34,656
[SPEAKER_19]: I've

339
00:24:34,636 --> 00:24:36,318
[SPEAKER_19]: kept Britain out of the Euro.

340
00:24:36,819 --> 00:24:47,153
[SPEAKER_19]: I can deliver these things in Europe, but I need your mandate, sir, in seven days' time to get out there and win a good deal for Britain that controls immigration and gets us a better position in Europe and with me.

341
00:24:47,613 --> 00:24:54,282
[SPEAKER_19]: You'll get that in-out referendum, you the British people deciding, before the end of 2017.

342
00:24:57,350 --> 00:24:58,592
[SPEAKER_41]: Good evening Mr Cameron.

343
00:24:59,253 --> 00:25:03,260
[SPEAKER_41]: I work in housing and I deal a lot with the homeless that live in Bradford.

344
00:25:03,961 --> 00:25:10,572
[SPEAKER_41]: A lot of those come from Eastern European countries who are not able to access those types of benefits that we're talking about.

345
00:25:11,293 --> 00:25:19,948
[SPEAKER_41]: What can the community do in relation to dealing with that because it does cause problems with relation to crime and drug substance misuse.

346
00:25:19,928 --> 00:25:27,741
[SPEAKER_19]: Well I think we need to go back to a system, much more, where of course you are free to travel around Europe to work in a different European country.

347
00:25:28,042 --> 00:25:31,768
[SPEAKER_19]: But you're not free simply to travel around Europe in order to claim benefits.

348
00:25:31,988 --> 00:25:35,715
[SPEAKER_19]: Freedom of movement was always meant to be about the freedom to go and take a job.

349
00:25:36,035 --> 00:25:38,119
[SPEAKER_19]: It was not freedom to go and claim benefits.

350
00:25:38,139 --> 00:25:39,922
[SPEAKER_19]: So those rules need to be tougher.

351
00:25:39,982 --> 00:25:43,067
[SPEAKER_19]: That's not what our benefits system is there for.

352
00:25:43,891 --> 00:25:52,710
[SPEAKER_32]: Yes, Mr Cameron, all of these questions you're being asked have a moral dimension and you keep answering them in terms of economics.

353
00:25:53,733 --> 00:25:58,423
[SPEAKER_32]: I'd like you to engage a little bit more with the moral dimension that these questions are asking.

354
00:26:05,542 --> 00:26:09,708
[SPEAKER_19]: To me, helping someone to get a job has a moral dimension.

355
00:26:09,808 --> 00:26:12,772
[SPEAKER_19]: It gives them the dignity and pride that comes with work.

356
00:26:12,792 --> 00:26:15,416
[SPEAKER_19]: Helping someone to get an apprenticeship, that has a moral dimension.

357
00:26:15,436 --> 00:26:18,019
[SPEAKER_19]: It gives someone the chance of a career and success.

358
00:26:18,480 --> 00:26:25,069
[SPEAKER_19]: Building a house that a young family can afford to buy and own, that's got a moral dimension because it gives them a stake in the country they live in.

359
00:26:25,049 --> 00:26:26,751
[SPEAKER_19]: That's the country I want to build.

360
00:26:26,791 --> 00:26:42,665
[SPEAKER_19]: These plans I've got for the next five years are about taking this economic foundation that we've built these last five years, all the shared sacrifice that we've been through, but not putting that to waste, but saying let's now turn that into jobs, into pay, into houses, into good school places.

361
00:26:43,005 --> 00:26:55,056
[SPEAKER_19]: And yes, also, into that sense at the end of your life that this is a country where if you work hard, you save and you do the right thing, you should get that dignity and security in retirement that I think is the right of everyone who lives in our country.

362
00:26:55,036 --> 00:27:10,463
[SPEAKER_46]: If you're in a situation where you have to team up with another party, what policies would you be willing to compromise?

363
00:27:13,902 --> 00:27:28,924
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm going to disappoint you because look we've got seven days to go and I'm going to fight everything I've got those next seven days to get an overall majority and the reason why I think that's right is look I think a strong decisive a more accountable government

364
00:27:28,904 --> 00:27:31,327
[SPEAKER_19]: where you're not trading away, that's the trouble with coalition.

365
00:27:31,627 --> 00:27:40,739
[SPEAKER_19]: You've got a great manifesto, you don't quite win the election, you go into some dark room with Nick Clegg or someone else and you start giving away some of the things that were in your programme.

366
00:27:40,759 --> 00:27:41,921
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't want to do that.

367
00:27:42,181 --> 00:27:49,410
[SPEAKER_19]: I think I've got a great programme about building these houses, creating these jobs, funding these apprenticeships, helping people with pensions.

368
00:27:49,390 --> 00:27:55,801
[SPEAKER_19]: And crucially, this European referendum, which I've said absolutely that is a red line, I don't want to give any of these things away.

369
00:27:55,962 --> 00:28:06,420
[SPEAKER_19]: So I'm going to spend the next seven days flat out for victory, and if enough people watching this programme are back at home, back me, we can have that victory and have the whole of the manifesto rather than have it bartered away in a darkened room.

370
00:28:06,400 --> 00:28:08,423
[SPEAKER_18]: But you talk about a darkened room.

371
00:28:08,463 --> 00:28:14,113
[SPEAKER_18]: What you said five years ago, we must sort things out as quickly as possible for the good of the country.

372
00:28:14,513 --> 00:28:18,380
[SPEAKER_18]: So I want to make a big, open, comprehensive offer to the Liberal Democrats.

373
00:28:18,440 --> 00:28:22,947
[SPEAKER_18]: Now it's getting closeted in a dark room with Nick Clegg.

374
00:28:22,967 --> 00:28:26,333
[SPEAKER_18]: That's what's happened.

375
00:28:26,971 --> 00:28:28,954
[SPEAKER_19]: I think it's completely consistent.

376
00:28:28,974 --> 00:28:31,297
[SPEAKER_19]: What I'm saying is that the last election wasn't decisive.

377
00:28:31,558 --> 00:28:37,647
[SPEAKER_19]: I believe I did the right thing by forming a coalition and having a decisive government to deal with the mess that we left.

378
00:28:37,727 --> 00:28:40,151
[SPEAKER_19]: But I'm saying this time I think we can go one better.

379
00:28:40,892 --> 00:28:51,848
[SPEAKER_19]: So I'm saying let's have a decisive outcome and these things don't have to be compromised on and we can have a really decisive government, more accountable government for you as a citizen.

380
00:28:52,469 --> 00:29:02,081
[SPEAKER_44]: Winning by a mile is a good hope, but say you don't, then what if you have to be in a coalition with somebody else?

381
00:29:02,942 --> 00:29:07,127
[SPEAKER_19]: Let me give one specific example of something I've been very clear about.

382
00:29:07,388 --> 00:29:15,198
[SPEAKER_19]: I think the British people really do deserve a referendum on whether to stay in a reformed European Union or leave.

383
00:29:15,218 --> 00:29:18,662
[SPEAKER_19]: And I've been very clear that I will not lead a government

384
00:29:18,642 --> 00:29:20,284
[SPEAKER_19]: that does not deliver that pledge.

385
00:29:20,325 --> 00:29:22,348
[SPEAKER_19]: So I couldn't be clearer about that red line.

386
00:29:22,368 --> 00:29:26,354
[SPEAKER_19]: Because I think people, frankly, have been let down too many times about this issue.

387
00:29:26,694 --> 00:29:37,370
[SPEAKER_19]: And I want everyone holding that stubby pencil in their hands in the voting booth in a week's time to know, if you get me as Prime Minister, you get that chance to have that in or out referendum.

388
00:29:37,651 --> 00:29:43,479
[SPEAKER_18]: So if you couldn't govern without the Liberal Democrats on those grounds, you wouldn't govern with them either?

389
00:29:43,499 --> 00:29:45,062
[SPEAKER_19]: Because they're not in favour of that.

390
00:29:45,082 --> 00:29:47,265
[SPEAKER_19]: You've correctly interpreted what I've said.

391
00:29:48,072 --> 00:29:50,916
[SPEAKER_19]: So what happens to the government of the country?

392
00:29:51,257 --> 00:30:08,062
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm saying, if I'm to form a government, and I hope to win the election in seven days' time, we're 23 seats short of an overall majority, and so I hope to govern the country as a majority, but if I don't, for whatever reason, I've been very clear, I would not lead a government that did not contain that pledge.

393
00:30:08,202 --> 00:30:08,843
[SPEAKER_19]: Couldn't be clearer.

394
00:30:09,004 --> 00:30:09,945
[SPEAKER_19]: Briefly you, sir.

395
00:30:10,145 --> 00:30:23,487
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't think you'd be more likely to actually win that overall majority if you treated voters with the intelligence they have and answered their questions in terms of what ifs and what might happen if there was a coalition that needed.

396
00:30:23,948 --> 00:30:25,630
[SPEAKER_02]: Treat people with their intelligence.

397
00:30:25,771 --> 00:30:27,934
[SPEAKER_19]: I think that it's fair

398
00:30:27,914 --> 00:30:31,138
[SPEAKER_19]: in the last seven days to do everything you can to try and win.

399
00:30:31,178 --> 00:30:39,267
[SPEAKER_19]: I want to use the limited time I've got, including the 28 minutes tonight, to explain why a Conservative majority government would be good for Britain.

400
00:30:39,287 --> 00:30:44,894
[SPEAKER_19]: I think we'd go further and faster in clearing the deficit, in building those homes, in providing those pensions.

401
00:30:45,114 --> 00:30:45,915
[SPEAKER_19]: That's what I want to do.

402
00:30:46,316 --> 00:30:48,338
[SPEAKER_18]: You've had your 28 minutes.

403
00:30:48,578 --> 00:30:49,780
[SPEAKER_19]: Let me make this point.

404
00:30:49,800 --> 00:30:52,403
[SPEAKER_19]: People know with me, if we fall short,

405
00:30:52,383 --> 00:30:53,885
[SPEAKER_19]: I will do the right thing for the country.

406
00:30:53,926 --> 00:31:07,387
[SPEAKER_19]: I did last time, I would again, but I would still plead with people with seven days to go, particularly when you're faced with the alternative of a Labour government backed by the SNP, people who don't even want our country to succeed or even exist.

407
00:31:07,688 --> 00:31:13,878
[SPEAKER_19]: When that's the alternative, put your trust in 23 more seats for the Conservatives and we can have a very strong and very clear government.

408
00:31:13,918 --> 00:31:16,382
[SPEAKER_19]: David Cameron, thank you very much indeed.

409
00:31:28,462 --> 00:31:34,227
[SPEAKER_18]: So, our next party leader is from the Labour Party.

410
00:31:34,247 --> 00:31:43,016
[SPEAKER_18]: The leader of the Labour Party, would you welcome Ed Miliband, please?

411
00:31:43,036 --> 00:31:50,583
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you very much.

412
00:31:50,603 --> 00:31:50,823
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

413
00:31:50,843 --> 00:31:53,686
[SPEAKER_18]: Mr Miliband, the first question is from Elizabeth Moody, please.

414
00:31:54,266 --> 00:31:55,127
[SPEAKER_18]: Elizabeth Moody.

415
00:31:55,630 --> 00:31:56,992
[SPEAKER_38]: Good evening, Mr Miliband.

416
00:31:57,733 --> 00:32:02,039
[SPEAKER_38]: Five years ago, the outgoing Labour Treasury Minister left a message.

417
00:32:02,480 --> 00:32:03,661
[SPEAKER_38]: There's no money left.

418
00:32:04,462 --> 00:32:07,707
[SPEAKER_38]: How can we trust the Labour Party with the UK economy?

419
00:32:08,067 --> 00:32:09,209
[SPEAKER_18]: We just saw it, by the way.

420
00:32:10,771 --> 00:32:14,637
[SPEAKER_17]: David Cameron carried it in his pocket and produced it.

421
00:32:14,657 --> 00:32:16,980
[SPEAKER_17]: I think it's his regular prop.

422
00:32:16,960 --> 00:32:20,265
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me directly address you, Elizabeth.

423
00:32:20,626 --> 00:32:22,309
[SPEAKER_17]: There was a global financial crisis.

424
00:32:22,549 --> 00:32:23,791
[SPEAKER_17]: There was a high deficit.

425
00:32:24,051 --> 00:32:25,594
[SPEAKER_17]: That deficit hasn't been cleared.

426
00:32:25,994 --> 00:32:30,462
[SPEAKER_17]: It will be the mission of my government to cut the deficit every year and balance the books.

427
00:32:30,762 --> 00:32:32,084
[SPEAKER_17]: And let me tell you how I'm going to do it.

428
00:32:32,585 --> 00:32:33,987
[SPEAKER_17]: First of all, we'll have fair taxes.

429
00:32:34,428 --> 00:32:38,755
[SPEAKER_17]: So we'll reverse David Cameron's tax cut for the richest in our society, millionaires.

430
00:32:39,235 --> 00:32:43,963
[SPEAKER_17]: I can't justify a £43,000 tax cut for every millionaire in Britain.

431
00:32:43,943 --> 00:32:52,232
[SPEAKER_17]: Secondly, we'll protect key areas like health and education, but outside those key areas there will be falls in spending because we've got to get the deficit down.

432
00:32:52,673 --> 00:32:54,955
[SPEAKER_17]: But the final thing concerns your living standards.

433
00:32:55,456 --> 00:32:57,478
[SPEAKER_17]: We've seen living standards fall over this Parliament.

434
00:32:57,898 --> 00:33:03,504
[SPEAKER_17]: As a result, lower living standards means lower tax revenues for government, and that's why the deficit hasn't been cleared.

435
00:33:03,885 --> 00:33:06,728
[SPEAKER_17]: So it's a three-part plan to make sure we balance the books.

436
00:33:06,708 --> 00:33:19,306
[SPEAKER_18]: But if you look back, and the question was looking back, why should we trust Labour in the light of what happened before, for six years before the crash, you increased borrowing, year on year on year on year.

437
00:33:19,847 --> 00:33:21,730
[SPEAKER_18]: So why should people believe that they're going to get it done?

438
00:33:21,810 --> 00:33:26,877
[SPEAKER_17]: The debt and the deficit were both lower before the financial crisis, but let me direct... Of course they were, but you were increasing

439
00:33:26,857 --> 00:33:29,864
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, let me address directly the issue about the financial crisis.

440
00:33:29,884 --> 00:33:31,447
[SPEAKER_17]: We got it wrong on bank regulation.

441
00:33:31,688 --> 00:33:36,679
[SPEAKER_17]: Look, the mistake we made, and I absolutely say this to this audience, was the banks weren't properly regulated.

442
00:33:37,120 --> 00:33:38,143
[SPEAKER_17]: We made that mistake.

443
00:33:38,584 --> 00:33:43,755
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, the question you've got to consider for the future is who's going to get it right for the future.

444
00:33:44,217 --> 00:33:45,760
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, we've learnt that lesson.

445
00:33:45,740 --> 00:33:49,448
[SPEAKER_17]: So happens David Cameron was saying there should be less bank regulation at a time, but leave that to one side.

446
00:33:49,729 --> 00:33:51,633
[SPEAKER_17]: We've learnt that lesson for the future.

447
00:33:52,194 --> 00:33:57,425
[SPEAKER_17]: And look, I'm the first Labour leader, David, going into an election saying spending in key areas is actually going to fall.

448
00:33:58,167 --> 00:34:05,082
[SPEAKER_17]: That's because I'm so determined, back to Elizabeth, that we live within our means.

449
00:34:07,880 --> 00:34:12,605
[SPEAKER_40]: Just getting back to your letter for a moment, the letter that Mr Cameron you call is a prop.

450
00:34:13,105 --> 00:34:14,627
[SPEAKER_40]: I run a business here in Leeds.

451
00:34:14,907 --> 00:34:19,492
[SPEAKER_40]: The last five years have been really hard work but we've got a plan now and the economy is improving.

452
00:34:19,792 --> 00:34:25,138
[SPEAKER_40]: What worries me is you're about to put Ed Balls back in as a Chancellor and he called that letter a joke.

453
00:34:25,518 --> 00:34:33,887
[SPEAKER_40]: Now let me tell you, running a business the last few years is anything but a joke and if that's the way your party wants to treat the economy, how can we trust you?

454
00:34:41,680 --> 00:34:43,924
[SPEAKER_17]: May I ask what your business does?

455
00:34:44,264 --> 00:34:45,486
[SPEAKER_40]: I run a marketing business.

456
00:34:45,506 --> 00:34:48,872
[SPEAKER_40]: I employ 76 people here in this city.

457
00:34:49,132 --> 00:34:53,439
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, let me tell you very specifically what I think we need to do for businesses like yours.

458
00:34:53,760 --> 00:34:56,244
[SPEAKER_17]: And this does go to the big choice at this election.

459
00:34:56,504 --> 00:35:04,618
[SPEAKER_17]: There'll be some people who tell you that the way we succeed as a country is as long as a few people at the top do well and large corporations, that's what powers the economy.

460
00:35:05,099 --> 00:35:08,464
[SPEAKER_17]: Look, I've got a different view and that's your choice for the next five years.

461
00:35:08,444 --> 00:35:12,648
[SPEAKER_17]: I think it's when working people, when every person in our country succeeds, that Britain succeeds.

462
00:35:12,668 --> 00:35:15,571
[SPEAKER_17]: Now for your business, we'd make a different choice from Mr Cameron.

463
00:35:15,932 --> 00:35:18,595
[SPEAKER_17]: He wants to cut taxes further for the largest businesses.

464
00:35:18,995 --> 00:35:21,117
[SPEAKER_17]: I would cut your business rates if I was Prime Minister.

465
00:35:21,558 --> 00:35:27,183
[SPEAKER_17]: Now that's important, I hope, for your business, but I think it tells a bigger story about how Britain succeeds.

466
00:35:27,464 --> 00:35:34,091
[SPEAKER_17]: And as I say, I think it succeeds not just with a few successful corporations, but with millions of businesses and millions of working people.

467
00:35:34,191 --> 00:35:35,532
[SPEAKER_18]: Does that satisfy you?

468
00:35:35,512 --> 00:35:36,094
[SPEAKER_40]: No it doesn't.

469
00:35:36,375 --> 00:35:37,618
[SPEAKER_40]: That wasn't the question I asked you.

470
00:35:37,659 --> 00:35:41,952
[SPEAKER_40]: I asked you why on earth I should trust a Chancellor who thinks a letter like that was a joke.

471
00:35:42,273 --> 00:35:47,268
[SPEAKER_40]: If he worked in the corporate world he would have been fired and he would not be allowed back to do that job.

472
00:35:47,549 --> 00:35:48,913
[SPEAKER_40]: And you're telling me he can do it.

473
00:35:52,268 --> 00:35:57,758
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me tell you, I can tell you, Ed Balls takes incredibly seriously the need to get the deficit down.

474
00:35:58,079 --> 00:36:00,764
[SPEAKER_17]: That was it while I was at the front page of our manifesto.

475
00:36:01,044 --> 00:36:07,496
[SPEAKER_17]: That's why he as Shadow Chancellor is going into this election telling all of our colleagues in lots of these departments that spending is going to fall.

476
00:36:07,516 --> 00:36:12,505
[SPEAKER_17]: You'll have to make your decision but we are absolutely deadly serious about getting the deficit down and balancing the books.

477
00:36:12,485 --> 00:36:15,172
[SPEAKER_40]: I also think, Mr Miliband, you talk about big businesses.

478
00:36:15,192 --> 00:36:18,921
[SPEAKER_40]: I was today with the biggest private employer in the UK, which is Tesco.

479
00:36:19,182 --> 00:36:23,874
[SPEAKER_40]: They've had a pretty tough time, but they talked about behaving their way out of the problems they've made.

480
00:36:24,255 --> 00:36:27,122
[SPEAKER_40]: And I think that's something that politicians have got to think about too.

481
00:36:27,824 --> 00:36:29,869
[SPEAKER_17]: We need strong big business in this country.

482
00:36:29,849 --> 00:36:32,552
[SPEAKER_17]: We do, and one thing, can I just come in on that David?

483
00:36:32,572 --> 00:36:32,793
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, yes.

484
00:36:32,813 --> 00:36:37,499
[SPEAKER_17]: But one thing I think business needs, and again this is a difference of view, I think we need to stay within the European Union.

485
00:36:37,899 --> 00:36:40,062
[SPEAKER_17]: Because I think it would be a disaster for our businesses.

486
00:36:40,262 --> 00:36:46,510
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, give David Cameron credit, he believes in us staying in the EU, but I'm afraid he's being dragged by his party to exit from the EU.

487
00:36:46,730 --> 00:36:53,499
[SPEAKER_17]: Now again, I've got to say to this audience, I've got to say to this audience, I think that would be a real problem for our country.

488
00:36:53,519 --> 00:36:56,262
[SPEAKER_17]: Alright, the woman up there at the back, yes.

489
00:36:56,242 --> 00:36:56,583
[SPEAKER_37]: Hi.

490
00:36:57,284 --> 00:37:06,721
[SPEAKER_37]: With all the rhetoric about non-DOMs and unpaid tax, if your party were in power, do you think you could ever bridge the gap between the richest and the poorest?

491
00:37:06,741 --> 00:37:07,282
[SPEAKER_17]: What's your name?

492
00:37:07,843 --> 00:37:08,323
[SPEAKER_37]: It's Shirley.

493
00:37:08,844 --> 00:37:09,145
[SPEAKER_17]: Shirley?

494
00:37:09,325 --> 00:37:09,566
[SPEAKER_37]: Yeah.

495
00:37:09,846 --> 00:37:12,531
[SPEAKER_17]: It's a great question, Shirley, and let me answer it directly.

496
00:37:12,831 --> 00:37:17,119
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, there's this rule that Shirley's referring to called the non-DOM rule.

497
00:37:17,099 --> 00:37:24,128
[SPEAKER_17]: Now some of you may know about it, some of you may not, but basically it means you can live here, work here, be permanently settled here, but not pay taxes here.

498
00:37:24,668 --> 00:37:27,512
[SPEAKER_17]: It's been in place, believe it or not, for 200 years.

499
00:37:27,792 --> 00:37:28,914
[SPEAKER_17]: That's 40 Prime Ministers.

500
00:37:29,314 --> 00:37:30,075
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm going to get rid of it.

501
00:37:30,556 --> 00:37:37,524
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm going to get rid of it because I believe in a country where there's one rule for all, not one rule for the rich and powerful and another rule for everybody else.

502
00:37:37,805 --> 00:37:39,467
[SPEAKER_17]: Now David Cameron wants to defend that rule.

503
00:37:39,847 --> 00:37:41,069
[SPEAKER_17]: Now I think he's wrong about that.

504
00:37:41,329 --> 00:37:46,836
[SPEAKER_17]: I think we've got to tackle tax avoidance wherever we find it and make people at the top live up to their responsibilities.

505
00:37:46,816 --> 00:37:52,766
[SPEAKER_18]: I hope we can...

506
00:37:52,787 --> 00:37:54,850
[SPEAKER_18]: I hope we can reach the man sitting right behind me here.

507
00:37:54,910 --> 00:37:55,111
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes.

508
00:37:55,411 --> 00:37:57,074
[SPEAKER_20]: So I've just got a really simple question.

509
00:37:57,114 --> 00:38:01,602
[SPEAKER_20]: Do you accept that when Labour was last in power it overspent?

510
00:38:02,037 --> 00:38:02,578
[SPEAKER_17]: No I don't.

511
00:38:03,279 --> 00:38:04,601
[SPEAKER_17]: And I know you may not agree with that.

512
00:38:05,803 --> 00:38:08,087
[SPEAKER_17]: But let me just say very clearly...

513
00:38:08,107 --> 00:38:09,029
[SPEAKER_18]: Even with all the borrowing?

514
00:38:09,409 --> 00:38:10,091
[SPEAKER_17]: You're on your own?

515
00:38:10,151 --> 00:38:10,511
[SPEAKER_17]: No I don't.

516
00:38:10,531 --> 00:38:11,112
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me tell you.

517
00:38:11,513 --> 00:38:13,997
[SPEAKER_17]: Because there are schools that have been rebuilt in our country.

518
00:38:14,398 --> 00:38:16,001
[SPEAKER_17]: There are hospitals that were rebuilt.

519
00:38:16,441 --> 00:38:20,468
[SPEAKER_17]: There were Sure Start centres that were built.

520
00:38:20,448 --> 00:38:21,609
[SPEAKER_17]: which would not have happened.

521
00:38:22,030 --> 00:38:23,512
[SPEAKER_17]: And so, look, I don't agree with that.

522
00:38:23,952 --> 00:38:25,874
[SPEAKER_17]: And let me just explain to you the way I see it.

523
00:38:26,275 --> 00:38:30,019
[SPEAKER_17]: There was a global financial crisis which caused the deficit to rise.

524
00:38:30,500 --> 00:38:35,326
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, look, President Obama isn't dealing with a high deficit because we built more schools and hospitals.

525
00:38:35,866 --> 00:38:40,131
[SPEAKER_17]: He's dealing with a high deficit because there was that global financial crisis.

526
00:38:40,652 --> 00:38:41,953
[SPEAKER_17]: But spending's got to fall.

527
00:38:41,973 --> 00:38:44,256
[SPEAKER_17]: I say to this gentleman here, spending's got to fall.

528
00:38:44,737 --> 00:38:46,218
[SPEAKER_17]: And that's why we will reduce spending.

529
00:38:46,419 --> 00:38:46,739
[SPEAKER_16]: All right.

530
00:38:46,759 --> 00:38:47,620
[SPEAKER_16]: And you, sir, there?

531
00:38:48,427 --> 00:38:51,051
[SPEAKER_16]: global financial crisis.

532
00:38:52,413 --> 00:38:53,575
[SPEAKER_16]: Australia didn't suffer this.

533
00:38:53,815 --> 00:38:54,957
[SPEAKER_16]: Canada didn't suffer this.

534
00:38:55,538 --> 00:38:57,281
[SPEAKER_16]: Some of the other major countries didn't suffer.

535
00:38:58,202 --> 00:39:06,074
[SPEAKER_16]: This country suffered because Gordon Brown sold gold just to prop up the social services.

536
00:39:06,094 --> 00:39:11,863
[SPEAKER_16]: How can you stand there and say you didn't overspend and end up bankrupting this country?

537
00:39:12,103 --> 00:39:14,267
[SPEAKER_16]: That is absolutely ludicrous.

538
00:39:14,527 --> 00:39:17,151
[SPEAKER_16]: You're frankly just lying.

539
00:39:20,084 --> 00:39:25,571
[SPEAKER_17]: I guess I'm not going to convince you, but... Well, you're not going to convince me, because the facts speak for themselves.

540
00:39:26,152 --> 00:39:28,715
[SPEAKER_16]: You stood there and said you didn't overspend.

541
00:39:29,295 --> 00:39:33,481
[SPEAKER_16]: If I get to the end of the week and I can't afford to buy a pint, I've overspent.

542
00:39:34,161 --> 00:39:35,623
[SPEAKER_16]: It means I haven't got any money left.

543
00:39:35,643 --> 00:39:35,783
[SPEAKER_08]: Sure.

544
00:39:36,464 --> 00:39:45,175
[SPEAKER_16]: We've got to the end of a government of 13 years, and during that 13-year period, you spent, spent, you sold gold when it was low.

545
00:39:45,556 --> 00:39:49,180
[SPEAKER_16]: If we still had the gold now, we'd be pretty much better off.

546
00:39:49,885 --> 00:39:52,990
[SPEAKER_16]: You can't stand that and say... Can I just come back on the point that you made?

547
00:39:53,010 --> 00:39:54,312
[SPEAKER_17]: I think I'm not going to convince you...

548
00:39:54,333 --> 00:39:57,758
[SPEAKER_18]: The point being that it's a millstone round what happened under the last government.

549
00:39:57,858 --> 00:40:03,027
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me come back on this because you said something very important which is that some other countries didn't suffer from that.

550
00:40:03,047 --> 00:40:05,852
[SPEAKER_17]: Now that's because they were less exposed to financial services.

551
00:40:05,832 --> 00:40:08,538
[SPEAKER_16]: No, I'm sorry, I mean financial services.

552
00:40:08,918 --> 00:40:14,390
[SPEAKER_16]: Financial services actually put millions and millions and millions of pounds into this country.

553
00:40:14,991 --> 00:40:21,985
[SPEAKER_16]: Millions of pounds, which you then spend, and you spend irresponsibly.

554
00:40:21,965 --> 00:40:25,691
[SPEAKER_17]: because I think that what we didn't do enough of was build up other industries as well.

555
00:40:25,711 --> 00:40:28,455
[SPEAKER_17]: Sure, financial services is important, including here in Leeds.

556
00:40:28,776 --> 00:40:35,266
[SPEAKER_17]: But look, the reality is that we didn't do enough on apprenticeships, we didn't do enough on a modern industrial policy, and we're not doing enough now.

557
00:40:35,786 --> 00:40:38,030
[SPEAKER_17]: Because you can't simply rely on one industry.

558
00:40:38,430 --> 00:40:44,940
[SPEAKER_17]: And so my point is that actually you need a more diverse industrial base, and that is also at stake in this election.

559
00:40:44,961 --> 00:40:45,642
[SPEAKER_18]: All right, I'll come to you.

560
00:40:45,842 --> 00:40:47,645
[SPEAKER_18]: We must keep moving around the audience here.

561
00:40:47,665 --> 00:40:49,187
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't want two or three people to...

562
00:40:49,370 --> 00:40:55,643
[SPEAKER_23]: If you can't accept that you overspent in the last government, then why on earth should we trust you not to do it again?

563
00:40:55,683 --> 00:41:04,881
[SPEAKER_23]: If you can't even realise that that's what you did, and they've cut the deficit by half, why should we trust you not to do the same thing if you can't even accept that you overspent?

564
00:41:06,329 --> 00:41:11,297
[SPEAKER_17]: You and other audience members, and it goes back to Elizabeth's question, will have to make a choice.

565
00:41:11,317 --> 00:41:14,001
[SPEAKER_17]: There are some parties in this election saying no cuts at all.

566
00:41:14,502 --> 00:41:15,263
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not saying that.

567
00:41:15,683 --> 00:41:19,369
[SPEAKER_17]: Mr Cameron, or he didn't say this earlier, wants to double the cuts next year.

568
00:41:19,409 --> 00:41:22,935
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not just the same cuts as in the last parliament, double the cuts.

569
00:41:23,335 --> 00:41:25,699
[SPEAKER_17]: Now I think that would be incredibly dangerous for our National Health Service.

570
00:41:25,719 --> 00:41:26,841
[SPEAKER_17]: Because you want to borrow more.

571
00:41:26,861 --> 00:41:32,910
[SPEAKER_23]: You're saying you don't want people from my age group to be in debt and yet you're committing to borrowing even more.

572
00:41:32,890 --> 00:41:36,897
[SPEAKER_17]: No, we're committing to a balance plan which balances the books, not going much further.

573
00:41:37,237 --> 00:41:48,936
[SPEAKER_17]: And I tried to set out what that balance plan is, but look, you and others will have to make a judgement about this, because I think we can balance the books without sacrificing our public services, without sacrificing tax credits.

574
00:41:48,956 --> 00:41:52,502
[SPEAKER_17]: Jenny asked a question earlier, the very first question of this programme, where is Jenny who asked?

575
00:41:52,482 --> 00:41:53,404
[SPEAKER_17]: who asked the question.

576
00:41:53,504 --> 00:41:53,705
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah.

577
00:41:54,026 --> 00:41:58,376
[SPEAKER_17]: Look, Jenny, I'm afraid David Cameron, he might have sounded like he answered your question, but he didn't.

578
00:41:58,717 --> 00:42:00,381
[SPEAKER_17]: But he didn't really give you a guarantee.

579
00:42:00,481 --> 00:42:02,004
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm going to give you that guarantee tonight.

580
00:42:02,325 --> 00:42:03,909
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not going to cut your tax credits.

581
00:42:04,150 --> 00:42:06,916
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not going to cut child benefit or means test it.

582
00:42:06,956 --> 00:42:09,462
[SPEAKER_17]: I think that would be the wrong thing to do for our country.

583
00:42:09,442 --> 00:42:13,087
[SPEAKER_17]: the wrong thing to do for family financing.

584
00:42:13,107 --> 00:42:20,798
[SPEAKER_17]: And I've got to say, after Mr Cameron's answers tonight, tax credits and child benefit are on the ballot paper of this election.

585
00:42:20,998 --> 00:42:26,105
[SPEAKER_17]: Because millions of families risk losing thousands of pounds because of the cuts plan that he has.

586
00:42:26,306 --> 00:42:28,449
[SPEAKER_17]: So yes, I do disagree with Mr Cameron.

587
00:42:28,689 --> 00:42:29,530
[SPEAKER_17]: I've got a different plan.

588
00:42:29,630 --> 00:42:31,713
[SPEAKER_18]: I think we should move on to another subject.

589
00:42:32,114 --> 00:42:33,676
[SPEAKER_18]: Simon Wilkinson, please.

590
00:42:34,037 --> 00:42:35,078
[SPEAKER_18]: Simon Wilkinson.

591
00:42:35,058 --> 00:42:41,777
[SPEAKER_33]: Why is the Labour Party misleading the country about having to do a deal with the SNP in the event of a minority Labour government?

592
00:42:47,815 --> 00:42:48,596
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me be plain.

593
00:42:48,896 --> 00:42:51,380
[SPEAKER_17]: We're not going to do a deal with the Scottish National Party.

594
00:42:51,740 --> 00:42:52,922
[SPEAKER_17]: We're not going to have a coalition.

595
00:42:53,323 --> 00:42:54,224
[SPEAKER_17]: We're not going to have a deal.

596
00:42:54,765 --> 00:42:56,186
[SPEAKER_17]: And let me just say this to you, Simon.

597
00:42:56,947 --> 00:43:03,316
[SPEAKER_17]: If it meant we weren't going to be in government, not doing a coalition, not having a deal, then so be it.

598
00:43:04,017 --> 00:43:08,283
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not going to sacrifice the future of our country, the unity of our country.

599
00:43:08,563 --> 00:43:13,951
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not going to give in to SNP demands around Trident, around the deficit, or anything like that.

600
00:43:14,191 --> 00:43:16,354
[SPEAKER_17]: So I just want to repeat this point to you.

601
00:43:16,334 --> 00:43:22,403
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not going to have a Labour government if it means deals or coalitions with the Scottish National Party.

602
00:43:22,543 --> 00:43:24,647
[SPEAKER_17]: And I just want to say this to voters in Scotland, David.

603
00:43:24,667 --> 00:43:28,012
[SPEAKER_17]: There's no easy route here to vote SNP and get a Labour government.

604
00:43:28,312 --> 00:43:30,595
[SPEAKER_17]: If you want a Labour government, you need to vote Labour.

605
00:43:31,176 --> 00:43:36,925
[SPEAKER_33]: So when other members of the Shadow Cabinet say that they're open to deals, you disagree with that?

606
00:43:36,905 --> 00:43:37,826
[SPEAKER_33]: I do, and I'm the leader.

607
00:43:38,086 --> 00:43:38,847
[SPEAKER_33]: We're not going to have deals.

608
00:43:38,867 --> 00:43:41,410
[SPEAKER_33]: And you wouldn't put forward a Queen's speech on the hope that they'd support it?

609
00:43:41,430 --> 00:43:44,954
[SPEAKER_33]: You just wouldn't go to the Queen and accept her invitation?

610
00:43:45,054 --> 00:43:46,816
[SPEAKER_33]: We do want to put forward a Labour Queen's speech.

611
00:43:46,876 --> 00:43:50,640
[SPEAKER_17]: I want a majority Labour government, and it'll be for parties in the House of Commons to vote for it.

612
00:43:50,840 --> 00:43:54,304
[SPEAKER_17]: But you ask me about deals, you ask me about coalitions, they're not going to happen.

613
00:43:54,484 --> 00:43:55,405
[SPEAKER_17]: I couldn't be clearer with you.

614
00:43:55,905 --> 00:43:57,167
[SPEAKER_18]: You said something rather interesting then.

615
00:43:57,187 --> 00:44:03,233
[SPEAKER_18]: You said you'd rather not have a Labour government than have a Labour government supported by the SNP?

616
00:44:03,213 --> 00:44:05,457
[SPEAKER_17]: A Labour government with a coalition or a deal?

617
00:44:05,497 --> 00:44:08,061
[SPEAKER_17]: What is a deal in your terms?

618
00:44:08,542 --> 00:44:10,445
[SPEAKER_17]: I've been asked about lots of different kinds of deals.

619
00:44:10,686 --> 00:44:13,050
[SPEAKER_17]: Coalition, what they call confidence and supply.

620
00:44:13,070 --> 00:44:15,314
[SPEAKER_17]: The coalition you've explained, which is ministers in your cabinet.

621
00:44:15,854 --> 00:44:16,596
[SPEAKER_17]: But what is a deal?

622
00:44:16,736 --> 00:44:20,603
[SPEAKER_17]: Confidence and supply, they've said, which is where you sort of have an arrangement.

623
00:44:20,743 --> 00:44:21,684
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not doing that.

624
00:44:21,905 --> 00:44:23,247
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not doing that.

625
00:44:23,362 --> 00:44:25,505
[SPEAKER_17]: And I want to explain why I'm not doing it.

626
00:44:25,545 --> 00:44:28,508
[SPEAKER_18]: So you'd rather lose office, so to speak.

627
00:44:28,528 --> 00:44:30,711
[SPEAKER_18]: You'd rather not have a Labour government than do that.

628
00:44:30,731 --> 00:44:35,657
[SPEAKER_17]: If the price of having a Labour government was a coalition or a deal with the Scottish National Party, it's not going to happen.

629
00:44:35,677 --> 00:44:36,018
[SPEAKER_18]: OK.

630
00:44:36,378 --> 00:44:36,899
[SPEAKER_18]: Anyone want to comment?

631
00:44:37,099 --> 00:44:37,960
[SPEAKER_18]: No, you've spoken already.

632
00:44:39,542 --> 00:44:41,504
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, you, sir, there, in the middle.

633
00:44:41,805 --> 00:44:43,387
[SPEAKER_18]: I'd like to have people who haven't spoken already.

634
00:44:43,427 --> 00:44:43,567
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes.

635
00:44:44,668 --> 00:44:47,772
[SPEAKER_13]: In that case, does that rule out a future Labour government?

636
00:44:48,153 --> 00:44:52,558
[SPEAKER_13]: Because you're not going to win the most seats in the UK.

637
00:44:53,534 --> 00:45:00,644
[SPEAKER_17]: First of all, I don't want to sound like the previous bloke, Mr Cameron, but I am working for a majority Labour government.

638
00:45:00,964 --> 00:45:08,094
[SPEAKER_17]: But look, I'm going to fight as hard as I can, for as many seats as I can, and then it'll be for the House of Commons to decide who's in government.

639
00:45:08,374 --> 00:45:12,480
[SPEAKER_17]: I just want to make this point about the SNP, and the same applies to a party like UKIP.

640
00:45:12,500 --> 00:45:14,383
[SPEAKER_17]: The reason why I reject the SNP...

641
00:45:14,423 --> 00:45:19,650
[SPEAKER_17]: I mean, they're, by the way, fighting us in Scotland, so the notion that we're sort of friends with the SNP is obviously nonsense.

642
00:45:19,670 --> 00:45:22,073
[SPEAKER_17]: They're our die-hard opponents.

643
00:45:22,053 --> 00:45:39,168
[SPEAKER_17]: the reason I reject it is because they want to break up the country and not only that they used to say that the referendum was a once-in-a-lifetime experience that's what they said before the last referendum and now Nicola Sturgeon is opening the door to another referendum in the next five years that's why I'm not going to have a coalition or a deal with them.

644
00:45:39,188 --> 00:45:40,551
[SPEAKER_17]: And the woman there on the gangway?

645
00:45:41,189 --> 00:45:49,825
[SPEAKER_21]: The problem is, you do sound a lot like the other guy, because both of you seem to not entertain the possibility that you might not get a majority, which is absolutely ridiculous.

646
00:45:50,366 --> 00:45:54,834
[SPEAKER_21]: And you really need to be honest with voters about what you might do in the event that you don't.

647
00:45:55,215 --> 00:45:56,237
[SPEAKER_17]: What was your name, I'm sorry?

648
00:45:56,377 --> 00:45:56,778
[SPEAKER_21]: Rebecca.

649
00:45:56,958 --> 00:46:02,809
[SPEAKER_17]: Rebecca, let me try and do better than the other guy on this one.

650
00:46:02,789 --> 00:46:09,875
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, he was saying at the end, David Cameron, that if you didn't get a majority, it meant this business of going into a darkened room with Nick Clegg.

651
00:46:09,895 --> 00:46:14,773
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, I don't like the sound of that at all, for a whole range of reasons.

652
00:46:16,947 --> 00:46:20,494
[SPEAKER_17]: But I don't like it for one particular reason.

653
00:46:21,035 --> 00:46:25,204
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm not going to start bartering away my manifesto, whatever the outcome of the election.

654
00:46:26,246 --> 00:46:29,112
[SPEAKER_17]: Even if I don't win a majority, I've got a manifesto.

655
00:46:29,833 --> 00:46:34,062
[SPEAKER_17]: Some of you may have read it, not that many people, but some people may have read it.

656
00:46:34,042 --> 00:46:35,323
[SPEAKER_17]: The manifesto's out there.

657
00:46:35,663 --> 00:46:43,070
[SPEAKER_17]: If I'm the Prime Minister, I'm going to do everything I can to get my manifesto, not start trading for Nick Clegg or anyone else's manifesto.

658
00:46:43,410 --> 00:46:45,832
[SPEAKER_17]: And so, you know, I think we're in a sort of new world in Britain.

659
00:46:45,892 --> 00:46:49,896
[SPEAKER_17]: It was the first coalition, obviously, this coalition, that they'd been for a long time.

660
00:46:50,376 --> 00:46:58,303
[SPEAKER_17]: But in my view, if we don't have a majority government, it is not about saying, go into a darkened room with somebody and then start lopping off bits of your manifesto.

661
00:46:58,583 --> 00:46:59,784
[SPEAKER_17]: That isn't what you're voting for.

662
00:46:59,824 --> 00:47:01,325
[SPEAKER_17]: That isn't what Labour voters are voting for.

663
00:47:01,566 --> 00:47:03,087
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not going to happen if I'm Prime Minister.

664
00:47:03,067 --> 00:47:04,872
[SPEAKER_18]: All right, we'll go to another subject.

665
00:47:04,972 --> 00:47:06,396
[SPEAKER_18]: Elisha Lynas, please.

666
00:47:06,497 --> 00:47:07,860
[SPEAKER_18]: Elisha Lynas.

667
00:47:07,880 --> 00:47:12,614
[SPEAKER_35]: What makes your view more important than the British people when it comes to the EU and an in-out referendum?

668
00:47:12,935 --> 00:47:13,657
[SPEAKER_17]: Where is Elisha?

669
00:47:13,677 --> 00:47:13,957
[SPEAKER_17]: Oh, there.

670
00:47:14,539 --> 00:47:15,803
[SPEAKER_35]: It's actually Elisha.

671
00:47:16,123 --> 00:47:16,244
[SPEAKER_17]: Sure.

672
00:47:16,264 --> 00:47:16,665
[SPEAKER_17]: Elisha.

673
00:47:16,886 --> 00:47:17,507
[SPEAKER_17]: Elisha.

674
00:47:17,527 --> 00:47:18,831
[SPEAKER_17]: Elisha.

675
00:47:19,756 --> 00:47:20,978
[SPEAKER_17]: It's about leadership, Alicia.

676
00:47:21,498 --> 00:47:23,841
[SPEAKER_17]: It's about leadership and what I want to achieve as Prime Minister.

677
00:47:24,783 --> 00:47:28,367
[SPEAKER_17]: When I look at the country, what do I think the biggest problems in the country are?

678
00:47:29,068 --> 00:47:32,713
[SPEAKER_17]: I think five years of wages falling behind bills and the threat it's going to happen again.

679
00:47:33,354 --> 00:47:36,518
[SPEAKER_17]: I think five years of young people thinking they're going to have a worse life than their parents.

680
00:47:36,999 --> 00:47:39,402
[SPEAKER_17]: And five years of an NHS in crisis.

681
00:47:39,382 --> 00:47:50,924
[SPEAKER_17]: And if I'm Prime Minister, in seven or eight days' time, I want to spend all of my energies on those issues, not on deciding whether we want to exit the European Union, which I think, frankly, would be a disaster for the country and would set us back.

682
00:47:50,944 --> 00:47:51,906
[SPEAKER_17]: But supposing she wants a voice vote?

683
00:47:51,926 --> 00:47:54,691
[SPEAKER_35]: Yeah, so your view is more important than mine and everybody else here?

684
00:47:54,711 --> 00:47:55,753
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, it isn't...

685
00:47:57,421 --> 00:48:02,811
[SPEAKER_17]: I do respect that point of view, but I don't agree with it, because I'm putting my view forward.

686
00:48:03,191 --> 00:48:05,756
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think one of the things you've got to do... Then let us put ours forward.

687
00:48:05,776 --> 00:48:07,399
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, you do at the general election.

688
00:48:07,779 --> 00:48:12,628
[SPEAKER_17]: And one of the things about leadership is you don't always do what the polls tell you to do.

689
00:48:12,608 --> 00:48:14,672
[SPEAKER_17]: You do what you think is the right thing for the country.

690
00:48:14,912 --> 00:48:32,305
[SPEAKER_17]: And I've got to level with you and level with the country that I don't think the right thing for our country to do now is to plunge ourselves into two years of debating whether to leave the EU when I've got to tell you that for jobs and the millions of jobs that depend on it, for businesses and for families, it will be a disaster.

691
00:48:32,285 --> 00:48:39,279
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, there's one thing I will say to you, which is if there's any further transfer of powers from Britain to the European Union, we would have a referendum.

692
00:48:39,299 --> 00:48:40,681
[SPEAKER_17]: I think it's unlikely to happen, though.

693
00:48:41,042 --> 00:48:44,949
[SPEAKER_17]: So, you know, in a way, you've got to make your own judgment about what is the most important issue to you.

694
00:48:45,290 --> 00:48:47,414
[SPEAKER_17]: For me, it isn't trying to get out of the EU.

695
00:48:48,276 --> 00:48:48,336
OK?

696
00:48:53,378 --> 00:49:00,397
[SPEAKER_48]: So you don't want an EU referendum and all the debate that brings, but a second election because you won't form a majority government?

697
00:49:00,798 --> 00:49:02,001
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't want a second election either.

698
00:49:02,463 --> 00:49:06,494
[SPEAKER_48]: Yeah, but if you don't get a majority, the Conservatives don't get a majority, you're not going to go with the SNP.

699
00:49:06,534 --> 00:49:07,175
[SPEAKER_48]: I want to govern.

700
00:49:07,516 --> 00:49:09,261
[SPEAKER_17]: I want to govern and change the country.

701
00:49:09,241 --> 00:49:13,228
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think, I've just got to say to you, the stakes are incredibly high.

702
00:49:13,849 --> 00:49:15,833
[SPEAKER_17]: You get this choice once every five years.

703
00:49:16,254 --> 00:49:24,168
[SPEAKER_17]: Do you want a country run for the richest and most powerful, the non-Doms that the lady talked about at the top, defending the non-Doms, while for Jenny, her tax credits aren't safe.

704
00:49:24,409 --> 00:49:25,711
[SPEAKER_17]: That's the choice at this election.

705
00:49:26,072 --> 00:49:27,575
[SPEAKER_18]: That is the choice facing the British people.

706
00:49:27,595 --> 00:49:28,156
[SPEAKER_18]: A couple more people.

707
00:49:28,176 --> 00:49:29,999
[SPEAKER_18]: The woman there and then I'll come to you and then we'll move on.

708
00:49:30,139 --> 00:49:30,540
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes.

709
00:49:31,550 --> 00:49:36,706
[SPEAKER_12]: The Conservative Party have made cuts to education, adults and further education.

710
00:49:37,148 --> 00:49:40,699
[SPEAKER_12]: How do you propose to undo the damage?

711
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:43,924
[SPEAKER_18]: You're on education, which we may come to.

712
00:49:44,084 --> 00:49:47,369
[SPEAKER_18]: I want to stick to the subject of the EU, if you don't mind, while we're on it.

713
00:49:47,469 --> 00:49:48,290
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, you, sir.

714
00:49:48,711 --> 00:49:48,951
[SPEAKER_15]: Hello.

715
00:49:48,971 --> 00:49:49,372
[SPEAKER_15]: Mr Miliband.

716
00:49:49,492 --> 00:49:49,952
[SPEAKER_15]: Hi.

717
00:49:49,972 --> 00:49:57,042
[SPEAKER_15]: Can I just ask you, you know when people ask you a question about forming a coalition, and you say, no, I want a majority, and Mr Cameron said the same.

718
00:49:57,903 --> 00:50:02,950
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you comprehend how much respect you would get from the audience if you were truly honest?

719
00:50:03,711 --> 00:50:05,674
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, look, sir, I'm saying to you...

720
00:50:07,696 --> 00:50:21,271
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm absolutely not saying to you I'm guaranteed a majority, I'm working for it, and I guess you'll respect me saying that, but I tried to answer the lady on the end who asked the question about the circumstances of not getting a majority, and I tried to outline my approach.

721
00:50:21,952 --> 00:50:26,897
[SPEAKER_17]: And as I said, my approach is not to start to barter away different bits of the manifesto.

722
00:50:27,158 --> 00:50:33,805
[SPEAKER_17]: And the reason I say that is because I think trust in politics, which is a pretty fragile thing anyway, is incredibly low.

723
00:50:33,785 --> 00:50:44,261
[SPEAKER_17]: And so the idea that Nick Clegg says, I'm breaking my tuition fees promise, and David Cameron says I'm breaking my VAT promise, and they blame each other and the coalition, that's not going to be my approach whatever the circumstances.

724
00:50:44,562 --> 00:50:47,506
[SPEAKER_17]: If I'm Prime Minister, I'm going to seek to implement all of my manifesto.

725
00:50:47,947 --> 00:50:50,551
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm going to go back to the lady there.

726
00:50:50,571 --> 00:50:53,295
[SPEAKER_18]: Just one brief question on this and an answer if you would.

727
00:50:54,743 --> 00:50:59,193
[SPEAKER_12]: Conservative Party have made up to 24% cuts in adults and further education.

728
00:50:59,233 --> 00:51:05,828
[SPEAKER_12]: How do you propose to undo the damage done by the savage cuts to adult education made by this government?

729
00:51:06,109 --> 00:51:07,091
[SPEAKER_17]: Have you had experience of this?

730
00:51:07,111 --> 00:51:07,612
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes, we have.

731
00:51:08,093 --> 00:51:08,955
[SPEAKER_12]: I work in FE.

732
00:51:09,661 --> 00:51:18,192
[SPEAKER_17]: What we've said for the future, I can't guarantee to reverse what's already been done, but what we've said for the future is that we will protect education spending.

733
00:51:18,613 --> 00:51:20,575
[SPEAKER_17]: So it will be protected at least against inflation.

734
00:51:21,056 --> 00:51:31,170
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, the reason why we've made that choice, which we haven't made in other government departments, is because I think investing in education, investing in the future, is essential not just for our society but for our economy as well.

735
00:51:31,510 --> 00:51:35,075
[SPEAKER_17]: Because I think it's a false economy to start cutting back on education spending.

736
00:51:35,235 --> 00:51:39,060
[SPEAKER_17]: So I can't promise to immediately reverse the damage and I'm not going to make a false promise to you.

737
00:51:39,040 --> 00:51:43,400
[SPEAKER_12]: That's for adults in further education, not for universities or primaries.

738
00:51:43,501 --> 00:51:47,700
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes indeed, we have made that point.

739
00:51:48,473 --> 00:51:52,259
[SPEAKER_28]: Mr. Miliband, is a vote for you carte blanche to see the Welfare Bill skyrocket?

740
00:51:52,279 --> 00:51:52,760
[SPEAKER_28]: I'm over here.

741
00:51:55,425 --> 00:51:56,046
[SPEAKER_17]: Hi, sorry.

742
00:51:56,346 --> 00:52:02,317
[SPEAKER_28]: It's OK. Is a vote for yourself, carte blanche, to see the Welfare Bill skyrocket?

743
00:52:02,337 --> 00:52:02,517
[SPEAKER_17]: No.

744
00:52:03,318 --> 00:52:05,582
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me explain why.

745
00:52:06,303 --> 00:52:08,527
[SPEAKER_17]: I believe in a welfare system with responsibility.

746
00:52:09,088 --> 00:52:12,574
[SPEAKER_17]: Responsibility means that if you can work, you should work.

747
00:52:12,554 --> 00:52:23,872
[SPEAKER_17]: We're the only party at this election actually putting forward a proposal to say if you're a young person unemployed more than a year, we'll guarantee you a job working with the private sector, but if you don't take the job you'll lose benefits.

748
00:52:24,413 --> 00:52:28,460
[SPEAKER_17]: Because I think that actually responsibility is the foundation of the welfare system.

749
00:52:28,480 --> 00:52:32,045
[SPEAKER_17]: But let me just say one other thing to you, Amy, because it's important for keeping control of the welfare bill.

750
00:52:32,807 --> 00:52:34,309
[SPEAKER_17]: Take the issue of housing benefit.

751
00:52:34,880 --> 00:52:40,528
[SPEAKER_17]: You may not be obvious, but the housing benefit bill has gone up a lot in the last five years for those in work.

752
00:52:40,928 --> 00:52:46,095
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, the reason for that is we have an economy based on low pay, and we're not building enough homes in our country.

753
00:52:46,676 --> 00:52:50,341
[SPEAKER_17]: That's why we'll have an £8 minimum wage, and that's why we'll build homes again in Britain.

754
00:52:50,641 --> 00:53:01,536
[SPEAKER_17]: You see, dealing with the welfare bill is about responsibility, but it's also about tackling the underlying factors that are driving the welfare bill up, like a low-pay economy that doesn't work for working people.

755
00:53:01,796 --> 00:53:03,739
[SPEAKER_17]: And you know, this is all connected.

756
00:53:03,719 --> 00:53:10,651
[SPEAKER_17]: Because our economy doesn't work for most people and works for the richest in our society, in my view, it means that the welfare bill is higher.

757
00:53:11,111 --> 00:53:14,998
[SPEAKER_17]: It means that people are having a harder life and working all the hours that God sends.

758
00:53:15,298 --> 00:53:16,480
[SPEAKER_17]: So we'll keep it under control.

759
00:53:16,701 --> 00:53:19,646
[SPEAKER_28]: But doesn't your party believe that benefits are a legitimate lifestyle choice?

760
00:53:19,726 --> 00:53:19,886
[SPEAKER_17]: No.

761
00:53:20,467 --> 00:53:21,529
[SPEAKER_28]: I think that they do.

762
00:53:21,769 --> 00:53:24,514
[SPEAKER_28]: You say about raising minimum wage and you're going to guarantee jobs.

763
00:53:25,155 --> 00:53:26,077
[SPEAKER_28]: I work in recruitment.

764
00:53:26,097 --> 00:53:27,499
[SPEAKER_28]: Where are those jobs going to come from?

765
00:53:27,817 --> 00:53:30,562
[SPEAKER_17]: They're going to come from working with the private sector to help create those jobs.

766
00:53:31,464 --> 00:53:35,712
[SPEAKER_17]: Apprenticeships for our young people, so that actually there are the skilled people that the private sector needs.

767
00:53:35,993 --> 00:53:39,179
[SPEAKER_17]: A proper industrial policy, which will help the private sector.

768
00:53:39,239 --> 00:53:43,728
[SPEAKER_17]: Cutting business rates, which will also help grow the economy and help grow jobs.

769
00:53:43,748 --> 00:53:46,613
[SPEAKER_17]: Leading in the big industries of the future, like green industry.

770
00:53:46,994 --> 00:53:48,677
[SPEAKER_17]: Take climate change for example.

771
00:53:48,657 --> 00:53:50,779
[SPEAKER_17]: Look, some people see that as a burden.

772
00:53:50,799 --> 00:53:57,567
[SPEAKER_17]: It isn't a burden, it's a necessity to tackle it, but it's a chance for us to lead as a country in one of the most important industries of the future.

773
00:53:57,607 --> 00:53:59,289
[SPEAKER_18]: Can we come back to welfare?

774
00:54:03,474 --> 00:54:07,659
[SPEAKER_18]: Is your plan to cut the welfare bill, to increase it or keep it as it is?

775
00:54:07,679 --> 00:54:10,942
[SPEAKER_17]: There's a cap on the welfare bill which the government has put in place, we're going to keep to within that cap.

776
00:54:11,102 --> 00:54:17,770
[SPEAKER_18]: Because the IFS says that your commitment to being tough on welfare amounts to almost nothing.

777
00:54:18,492 --> 00:54:19,913
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I don't agree with them.

778
00:54:20,214 --> 00:54:21,114
[SPEAKER_18]: Where have they gone wrong?

779
00:54:21,275 --> 00:54:24,918
[SPEAKER_17]: Because they've analysed everybody's thing, everybody's spending, everybody's child.

780
00:54:24,938 --> 00:54:26,740
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me give you an example.

781
00:54:27,120 --> 00:54:29,582
[SPEAKER_17]: Look, you know, I want to help pensioners in our country.

782
00:54:29,602 --> 00:54:31,644
[SPEAKER_17]: We're going to have the triple lock on the basic state pension.

783
00:54:31,664 --> 00:54:34,447
[SPEAKER_17]: That means pensions going up by 2.5% or prices or earnings.

784
00:54:34,467 --> 00:54:40,813
[SPEAKER_17]: But we have said that the winter fuel allowance will not continue to go to pensioners with incomes above £43,000 a year.

785
00:54:41,313 --> 00:54:43,736
[SPEAKER_17]: Because I don't think I can justify that in the times that we're in.

786
00:54:43,916 --> 00:54:45,057
[SPEAKER_17]: But I think this point about the

787
00:54:45,037 --> 00:54:50,824
[SPEAKER_17]: drivers of the welfare bill and what is actually making it go up is actually the key thing that is underlying it.

788
00:54:50,944 --> 00:54:52,386
[SPEAKER_18]: I'll go to the woman with spectacles there at the back.

789
00:54:52,426 --> 00:54:54,368
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm trying to go to different people who haven't spoken yet.

790
00:54:54,428 --> 00:55:13,491
[SPEAKER_42]: Are you essentially telling us that you're expecting the private sector to fund the gaps in the welfare bill because there's only so much that employers can actually do to, you know, you can't keep expecting, you're talking about zero hours contracts, changes, you're talking about

791
00:55:14,315 --> 00:55:18,901
[SPEAKER_42]: getting people on to working in the private sector after a year.

792
00:55:18,961 --> 00:55:23,087
[SPEAKER_42]: How are employers supposed to afford all of this stuff?

793
00:55:23,268 --> 00:55:28,575
[SPEAKER_42]: Because being an employer is a very, very expensive business as it is.

794
00:55:29,096 --> 00:55:32,360
[SPEAKER_17]: We're definitely not expecting employers to fund the welfare bill.

795
00:55:32,701 --> 00:55:40,812
[SPEAKER_17]: But my point at the moment is that the welfare bill is actually spending billions and billions of pounds subsidising low pay in our country.

796
00:55:40,792 --> 00:55:42,314
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm afraid that's the sort of reality.

797
00:55:42,354 --> 00:55:49,561
[SPEAKER_17]: Now we've got to raise the minimum wage in a way that is cautious, because we've got to do it so it doesn't put people out of work, and that's what we'll do.

798
00:55:49,921 --> 00:55:58,330
[SPEAKER_17]: But I think we've also got to confront the fact that because we're one of the low-pay capitals of Europe, we are spending tens of billions of pounds on welfare as a result of that.

799
00:55:58,570 --> 00:56:01,573
[SPEAKER_17]: So it's about working with the private sector to make sure you can raise wages.

800
00:56:01,593 --> 00:56:04,096
[SPEAKER_17]: Alright, on that point let me bring in Chris Magee, please.

801
00:56:04,236 --> 00:56:05,517
[SPEAKER_18]: Chris Magee.

802
00:56:05,497 --> 00:56:09,443
[SPEAKER_11]: A ban on zero-hours contracts will prevent me from growing my small business.

803
00:56:10,144 --> 00:56:13,429
[SPEAKER_11]: Isn't it time the Labour Party put business before gimmicks and soundbites?

804
00:56:13,850 --> 00:56:23,063
[SPEAKER_18]: And there is evidence that more people like zero-hours contracts than dislike them.

805
00:56:23,083 --> 00:56:23,965
[SPEAKER_18]: Chris, what's your business?

806
00:56:24,245 --> 00:56:27,069
[SPEAKER_11]: It's a tourism business, so when the sun shines, I've got business.

807
00:56:27,210 --> 00:56:30,154
[SPEAKER_11]: If the sun doesn't shine, I don't, so...

808
00:56:30,455 --> 00:56:32,938
[SPEAKER_11]: The sun always shines in Yorkshire.

809
00:56:32,959 --> 00:56:33,419
[SPEAKER_17]: Yeah, always.

810
00:56:33,900 --> 00:56:35,542
[SPEAKER_17]: Whenever there's a cycle race, there is.

811
00:56:36,163 --> 00:56:40,189
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, let me tell you about our policy, Chris, and then maybe you come back and say how it might affect you.

812
00:56:40,589 --> 00:56:51,805
[SPEAKER_17]: Our policy is this, which is that after 12 weeks, an employee will have a right to a regular contract, not a zero-hours contract, based on the average number of hours that they've done.

813
00:56:51,785 --> 00:56:58,795
[SPEAKER_17]: And if the employee wants to carry on with the zero-hours contract, they can, but we think that should be in the hands of the employee having the right to the regular contract.

814
00:56:58,975 --> 00:57:00,638
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me just explain why I say that.

815
00:57:01,178 --> 00:57:04,142
[SPEAKER_17]: And I know this may be difficult for your business, but let me just explain the reasons for that.

816
00:57:04,703 --> 00:57:16,560
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't think we can base the future of our economy on the idea, and I meet lots of people on zero-hours contracts, that people don't know from one day to the next how many hours they're doing or what wage they're going to be getting.

817
00:57:16,540 --> 00:57:21,526
[SPEAKER_17]: Because I don't... Mr Cameron was honest enough to say the other day he couldn't live on a zero-hours contract.

818
00:57:21,846 --> 00:57:22,607
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, nor could I.

819
00:57:23,047 --> 00:57:26,751
[SPEAKER_17]: But if I can't live on it and he can't live on it, I don't think we should make the British people live on one.

820
00:57:26,851 --> 00:57:27,092
[SPEAKER_17]: All right.

821
00:57:27,272 --> 00:57:36,102
[SPEAKER_17]: One last question, if we can... That's the logic of my position.

822
00:57:36,122 --> 00:57:37,784
[SPEAKER_18]: Ryan... Ryan Furlong, please.

823
00:57:39,305 --> 00:57:39,405
[SPEAKER_11]: Hi.

824
00:57:40,146 --> 00:57:42,649
[SPEAKER_11]: What are you going to do differently about immigration?

825
00:57:43,355 --> 00:57:46,902
[SPEAKER_17]: I've changed Labour's position and let me tell you what we're going to do.

826
00:57:46,983 --> 00:57:51,369
[SPEAKER_17]: Under a Labour government, when people come here, they won't get benefits for at least the first two years.

827
00:57:52,170 --> 00:57:55,695
[SPEAKER_17]: We're going to ensure that in our public services, people learn English.

828
00:57:55,755 --> 00:57:58,379
[SPEAKER_17]: In fact, I think everybody who comes here should learn English.

829
00:57:59,060 --> 00:58:10,556
[SPEAKER_17]: And thirdly, we're going to stop something which I think, frankly, should have been stopped a long time ago, which is employers bringing people into this country, exploiting migrant labour, and undercutting wages.

830
00:58:10,876 --> 00:58:11,958
[SPEAKER_17]: Let me just give you a fact, Brian.

831
00:58:12,338 --> 00:58:14,982
[SPEAKER_17]: There have been...

832
00:58:16,092 --> 00:58:21,339
[SPEAKER_17]: There have been two prosecutions for failure to pay the minimum wage in the last five years.

833
00:58:22,040 --> 00:58:26,666
[SPEAKER_17]: Now, the notion that that reflects what's actually happening in the world of work is, of course, nonsense.

834
00:58:26,686 --> 00:58:32,593
[SPEAKER_17]: And even the government's own Migration Advisory Committee have said that is one of the things that is bringing low-skilled labour into here.

835
00:58:32,773 --> 00:58:40,403
[SPEAKER_17]: The notion that some rogue employers, and I emphasize some because most employers don't do this, can get away with bringing migrant labour in and undercutting wages.

836
00:58:40,683 --> 00:58:43,467
[SPEAKER_17]: So, the last thing I want to say to you is this.

837
00:58:43,447 --> 00:58:45,713
[SPEAKER_17]: You know, I don't believe it's prejudice to worry about immigration.

838
00:58:46,155 --> 00:58:47,699
[SPEAKER_17]: Some people say it is, I don't believe it is.

839
00:58:47,719 --> 00:58:48,943
[SPEAKER_17]: I think people's concerns are real.

840
00:58:49,264 --> 00:58:53,736
[SPEAKER_17]: I see it in my own constituency in Doncaster and we're going to deal with people's concerns with real controls.

841
00:58:56,083 --> 00:58:58,249
[SPEAKER_18]: Why won't you set a target then?

842
00:58:58,398 --> 00:59:07,653
[SPEAKER_25]: refused to set a target when she criticises the Conservative policy on it but isn't willing to commit to any kind of number at all.

843
00:59:07,793 --> 00:59:08,814
[SPEAKER_25]: Is it just free-for-all?

844
00:59:08,834 --> 00:59:16,507
[SPEAKER_25]: Everyone who wants to come here can come here regardless of economic suitability or affordability and where is everyone going to live?

845
00:59:21,354 --> 00:59:21,995
[SPEAKER_17]: What's your name?

846
00:59:22,616 --> 00:59:23,157
[SPEAKER_25]: Jo.

847
00:59:23,457 --> 00:59:33,695
[SPEAKER_17]: Joe, I'll tell you why I'm not going to set a target, because I don't want to stand on the stage in five years' time and try and explain why I've broken my promise.

848
00:59:33,715 --> 00:59:35,038
[SPEAKER_17]: This is a really important point.

849
00:59:35,639 --> 00:59:40,147
[SPEAKER_17]: David Cameron stood on the stage five years ago and said he'd get net migration to the tens of thousands.

850
00:59:40,407 --> 00:59:42,090
[SPEAKER_17]: It's now 298,000.

851
00:59:42,070 --> 00:59:44,312
[SPEAKER_17]: Let him answer Joe.

852
00:59:45,033 --> 00:59:47,616
[SPEAKER_17]: Because Joe, I'm not going to pluck a target out of the air.

853
00:59:47,636 --> 00:59:48,877
[SPEAKER_17]: It's not the right thing to do.

854
00:59:49,257 --> 00:59:51,319
[SPEAKER_17]: Because I can't guarantee I'm going to meet it.

855
00:59:51,340 --> 00:59:54,303
[SPEAKER_17]: And you know, this goes to a point about trust in politics.

856
00:59:54,603 --> 01:00:00,229
[SPEAKER_17]: Trust is so low in politics, for reasons I understand, because of broken promises in the past.

857
01:00:00,249 --> 01:00:06,475
[SPEAKER_17]: I want to be the first politician to under-promise and over-deliver, not over-promise and under-deliver.

858
01:00:06,978 --> 01:00:16,899
[SPEAKER_17]: And look, sometimes that means I'll get a hard time from people like Joe because I'm not making the easy promise.

859
01:00:17,160 --> 01:00:19,444
[SPEAKER_17]: But I'm not the guy who's going to make the easy promises.

860
01:00:19,725 --> 01:00:24,936
[SPEAKER_17]: Because all it does is it makes people think you're all going to break your promises.

861
01:00:25,220 --> 01:00:27,867
[SPEAKER_18]: All right, we've got... No, no, no, I'm afraid...

862
01:00:28,648 --> 01:00:32,237
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm afraid we've come to the end of those 28 minutes that he's had.

863
01:00:32,257 --> 01:00:33,601
[SPEAKER_17]: It flew by for me, anyway.

864
01:00:33,821 --> 01:00:34,844
[SPEAKER_17]: Maybe not for the audience.

865
01:00:34,864 --> 01:00:36,027
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you very much, Mr Lelen.

866
01:00:36,047 --> 01:00:37,390
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

867
01:00:49,503 --> 01:01:07,232
[SPEAKER_18]: So the last of our three leaders now from the Liberal Democrat party, the leader of the Liberal Democrats, would you welcome Nick Clegg.

868
01:01:07,253 --> 01:01:10,899
[SPEAKER_18]: And Mr Clegg, the first question comes from Darren Metcalfe, please.

869
01:01:10,919 --> 01:01:11,940
[SPEAKER_18]: Darren Metcalfe.

870
01:01:11,960 --> 01:01:13,583
[SPEAKER_08]: Nick.

871
01:01:13,603 --> 01:01:13,944
[SPEAKER_08]: Hi Darren.

872
01:01:14,264 --> 01:01:14,785
[SPEAKER_08]: Hiya.

873
01:01:15,389 --> 01:01:18,937
[SPEAKER_08]: Your promise on student loans has destroyed your reputation.

874
01:01:19,519 --> 01:01:30,765
[SPEAKER_20]: Why would we ever believe anything else you say?

875
01:01:30,948 --> 01:01:48,822
[SPEAKER_20]: look firstly I got it wrong I said sorry musically no less I when you make a mistake in politics just as in life in politics just as in life sometimes you can't do exactly what you want I was absolutely between a rock and a hard place five years ago on that particular policy secondly I hope you can

876
01:01:48,802 --> 01:02:13,769
[SPEAKER_20]: You can at least give me credit for the many, many other things that I have actually put into practice, whether it's taking lots of people on low pay out of paying any income tax, the biggest expansion of apprenticeships this country's ever seen, the biggest reform of our pension system in a generation, more money into schools to help with the education of disadvantaged children, more childcare, shared parental leave, healthy lunches for little kids at primary school, the list goes on.

877
01:02:14,049 --> 01:02:17,813
[SPEAKER_20]: Look, I accept that for some people, and you may be one of them,

878
01:02:17,793 --> 01:02:32,815
[SPEAKER_18]: for whom that one thing you can't forgive, you can't forget.

879
01:02:32,795 --> 01:02:37,561
[SPEAKER_20]: What happened, as you may remember, was the previous government, the Labour government, introduced fees and then increased them.

880
01:02:37,861 --> 01:02:39,523
[SPEAKER_20]: When we came into government, there was no money left.

881
01:02:39,823 --> 01:02:47,292
[SPEAKER_20]: David Cameron's just been waving around the letter which was provided to the Liberal Democrat Chief Secretary of the Treasury at the time, saying there was no money left.

882
01:02:47,392 --> 01:02:54,761
[SPEAKER_20]: And both the larger parties, as they, I think, would admit if you'd asked them about it, wanted fees to go up very, very considerably.

883
01:02:54,781 --> 01:03:00,608
[SPEAKER_20]: In fact, the report commissioned at the time into all of this said there should be no upper limit at all.

884
01:03:00,588 --> 01:03:08,038
[SPEAKER_20]: In a sense what we did was get the fairest deal we could in those circumstances and thankfully now got more young people at university than ever before.

885
01:03:08,239 --> 01:03:13,966
[SPEAKER_20]: But look, as I said earlier, my experience is some people absolutely will say, you know, we can't forget that.

886
01:03:13,986 --> 01:03:24,621
[SPEAKER_20]: I hope there are plenty of other fair-minded folk who will accept that nonetheless there are many, many, many other good policies that I did put into practice.

887
01:03:26,187 --> 01:03:27,148
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, you in the centre.

888
01:03:28,090 --> 01:03:47,858
[SPEAKER_07]: The policy of increasing tuition fees is essentially robbing from the rich to give them a sense of you're taking money away from future generations to go to university because the economy is going to be so bust by people not repaying their fees, never getting enough money to be able to meet the threshold, that the policy itself is completely defunct.

889
01:03:48,175 --> 01:03:49,117
[SPEAKER_20]: No, I don't agree with that.

890
01:03:49,879 --> 01:03:51,744
[SPEAKER_20]: No, I don't agree with that.

891
01:03:51,764 --> 01:03:57,839
[SPEAKER_20]: Under the old system we inherited, if you left university you had to start repaying the moment you earned £15,000.

892
01:03:58,100 --> 01:04:01,188
[SPEAKER_20]: Now you don't pay back if you earn 16, 17, 18, 19, 20.

893
01:04:01,488 --> 01:04:03,754
[SPEAKER_20]: You only start paying back when you earn... That's precisely my point.

894
01:04:03,734 --> 01:04:04,516
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, no.

895
01:04:04,536 --> 01:04:05,297
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, you're right.

896
01:04:06,500 --> 01:04:07,762
[SPEAKER_20]: Some people say it's not generous enough.

897
01:04:07,782 --> 01:04:08,784
[SPEAKER_20]: You're saying it's too generous.

898
01:04:09,005 --> 01:04:11,850
[SPEAKER_20]: You're right to say that no one needs to pay up front.

899
01:04:12,111 --> 01:04:17,622
[SPEAKER_20]: There were thousands of students under the old system who used to have to pay up front or ask their parents to do so.

900
01:04:17,942 --> 01:04:22,772
[SPEAKER_20]: And crucially, if you can't pay it off during your working life, it gets paid off for you.

901
01:04:22,752 --> 01:04:26,116
[SPEAKER_20]: So, in a sense, it's a much, much more fair system.

902
01:04:26,197 --> 01:04:31,404
[SPEAKER_20]: It's not the system I would have liked, but it's a much, much more fair system than people alleged at the time when it was introduced.

903
01:04:31,464 --> 01:04:33,166
[SPEAKER_18]: The question was about trust.

904
01:04:33,486 --> 01:04:35,809
[SPEAKER_18]: You, sir, in the blue pullover there with the tie.

905
01:04:35,829 --> 01:04:36,050
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes.

906
01:04:36,270 --> 01:04:37,211
[SPEAKER_18]: In the second row from the back.

907
01:04:37,271 --> 01:04:37,452
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

908
01:04:37,532 --> 01:04:38,132
[SPEAKER_10]: Hi, Mr. Clegg.

909
01:04:38,473 --> 01:04:38,613
[SPEAKER_10]: Hi.

910
01:04:38,753 --> 01:04:40,035
[SPEAKER_10]: The public suggests they can't forgive...

911
01:04:40,055 --> 01:04:41,537
[SPEAKER_18]: So, Prime Minister Clegg...

912
01:04:41,517 --> 01:04:42,118
[SPEAKER_10]: No.

913
01:04:44,100 --> 01:04:45,862
[SPEAKER_18]: I thought you said Prime Minister Clegg for a moment.

914
01:04:46,242 --> 01:04:48,224
[SPEAKER_10]: The public suggests they can't forgive that one thing.

915
01:04:48,524 --> 01:04:51,227
[SPEAKER_10]: So if hindsight, would you go into coalition in 2010 again?

916
01:04:52,228 --> 01:04:52,889
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, absolutely.

917
01:04:54,150 --> 01:04:59,055
[SPEAKER_20]: In fact, the more I look back on it, the more proud I am that I think it was a difficult decision.

918
01:04:59,075 --> 01:05:02,259
[SPEAKER_20]: I think it was a brave decision for the Liberal Democrats.

919
01:05:02,539 --> 01:05:04,301
[SPEAKER_20]: It's come at short-term political cost.

920
01:05:04,661 --> 01:05:10,107
[SPEAKER_20]: But I'm absolutely clear in my mind that if you think back to 2010, we could have been Greece.

921
01:05:10,087 --> 01:05:10,949
[SPEAKER_20]: We could have been Greece.

922
01:05:10,989 --> 01:05:12,652
[SPEAKER_20]: Our deficit was almost as big as Greece's.

923
01:05:12,772 --> 01:05:15,097
[SPEAKER_20]: Our banking crisis was a whole lot worse.

924
01:05:15,398 --> 01:05:29,767
[SPEAKER_20]: And I certainly wouldn't have wanted on my conscience higher interest rates, higher unemployment, higher youth unemployment, which I'm absolutely sure would have happened if we hadn't stepped up to the plate to create a stable government, without which an economic recovery is not possible.

925
01:05:29,787 --> 01:05:31,791
[SPEAKER_20]: And my great concern at the moment

926
01:05:31,771 --> 01:05:52,543
[SPEAKER_20]: is that having got this far over five years and millions of people across the country having made huge sacrifices to get us this far after that terrible heart attack in our economy back in 2008, that we undo it all by lurching off to the right with ideological hardline cuts or lurching off to the left borrowing pots of money that we can't afford.

927
01:05:52,584 --> 01:05:59,314
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we need to remain anchored in the centre ground so that we can finish the job of balancing the books but do it fairly.

928
01:05:59,294 --> 01:06:05,367
[SPEAKER_18]: All right, well, let's deal with where the Liberal Democrats might be with a question from Bethany Cowling, please, after this election.

929
01:06:05,387 --> 01:06:05,748
[SPEAKER_18]: Bethany.

930
01:06:05,828 --> 01:06:06,269
[SPEAKER_27]: Good evening.

931
01:06:07,131 --> 01:06:12,943
[SPEAKER_27]: Is leaking details that you're only privy to as part of a coalition likely to get you invited into a coalition again?

932
01:06:13,705 --> 01:06:14,687
[SPEAKER_16]: What are you referring to?

933
01:06:16,118 --> 01:06:21,845
[SPEAKER_27]: So, some details have been leaked today about a policy that was put forward by the Conservatives whilst you were in coalition with them.

934
01:06:21,865 --> 01:06:22,246
[SPEAKER_20]: It's hardly leaked.

935
01:06:22,266 --> 01:06:23,707
[SPEAKER_20]: Danny Alexander said it to The Nation.

936
01:06:23,767 --> 01:06:41,629
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, he's just saying, quite rightly, that unless the Conservatives come clean, and I don't think David Cameron's done it this evening, where they're going to take the equivalent of £1,500 off eight million of the most vulnerable families, we can only assume that they're looking at the kind of plans which they floated some years ago.

937
01:06:41,649 --> 01:06:42,671
[SPEAKER_20]: If they're ruling that out now...

938
01:06:42,691 --> 01:06:44,573
[SPEAKER_18]: Sorry, did you know about it when it happened?

939
01:06:44,553 --> 01:06:45,894
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, but if they're ruling that out...

940
01:06:45,914 --> 01:06:48,537
[SPEAKER_18]: But we didn't know, it only came out today, that's what she means.

941
01:06:48,557 --> 01:06:48,918
[SPEAKER_18]: Oh, I see.

942
01:06:49,058 --> 01:06:57,286
[SPEAKER_18]: It was something you discovered and worked on in coalition, which is being kept secret until today, when Danny Alexander suddenly announced it as a way of attacking the Tory party.

943
01:06:57,306 --> 01:07:11,421
[SPEAKER_20]: Last autumn, George Osborne made a speech at the Conservative Party conference, and he said that the Conservative Party, in a radical departure from the sensible way which we have adopted over the last five years to...

944
01:07:11,401 --> 01:07:22,131
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm not going to ask the very wealthy in society to pay a single extra penny in tax to balance the books and instead only the working age poor are going to pick up the tab for the mistakes made by the bankers.

945
01:07:22,491 --> 01:07:23,392
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that's unfair.

946
01:07:23,652 --> 01:07:29,637
[SPEAKER_20]: They've said they want to take the equivalent of £1,500 off the 8 million poorest families in this country.

947
01:07:29,918 --> 01:07:32,019
[SPEAKER_20]: They won't tell you how they'll do that.

948
01:07:32,039 --> 01:07:36,724
[SPEAKER_20]: £12 billion is about exactly as much as we spend as a country on disability living allowance.

949
01:07:36,744 --> 01:07:38,225
[SPEAKER_20]: Are they going to scrap disability allowance?

950
01:07:38,465 --> 01:07:40,547
[SPEAKER_20]: They're not going to touch child benefit.

951
01:07:40,527 --> 01:07:43,109
[SPEAKER_20]: Are they going to scrap this allowance?

952
01:07:43,130 --> 01:07:46,273
[SPEAKER_20]: It's about the same as we spend on employment support allowance.

953
01:07:46,393 --> 01:07:47,294
[SPEAKER_20]: Are they going to scrap that?

954
01:07:47,554 --> 01:07:53,179
[SPEAKER_20]: I think the point that Danny was making, quite rightly, is we've had five weeks of this election campaign.

955
01:07:53,519 --> 01:07:58,684
[SPEAKER_20]: The Conservatives have a very unfair plan to balance the books, which departs from what we've done in coalition.

956
01:07:58,945 --> 01:08:01,948
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think we are entitled to say, what are you going to do?

957
01:08:02,088 --> 01:08:02,788
[SPEAKER_20]: Who are you going to hurt?

958
01:08:03,069 --> 01:08:04,470
[SPEAKER_20]: Who is going to bear the pain?

959
01:08:04,850 --> 01:08:06,552
[SPEAKER_20]: OK, the woman up there, the back row.

960
01:08:06,532 --> 01:08:10,504
[SPEAKER_26]: But I don't think voters want to hear reasons why not to vote for another party.

961
01:08:10,865 --> 01:08:19,933
[SPEAKER_26]: We want reasons why to vote for your party.

962
01:08:20,555 --> 01:08:23,458
[SPEAKER_20]: That's fair, but I think also voters want to know what the choices are.

963
01:08:23,498 --> 01:08:40,156
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think at the moment the fundamental choices are a Conservative plan, as I've just described, which I think wants to balance the books, which we must do, but wants to do so unfairly, and a Labour plan, which still won't give you any timetable or any detail or any plan about how to balance the books in the first place.

964
01:08:40,176 --> 01:08:49,566
[SPEAKER_20]: I think one of the most important things, whoever is in government, in whatever combination, and by the way, unlike Ed Binnaban and David Cameron, alas, I'm not pretending I'm going to be Prime Minister.

965
01:08:49,546 --> 01:09:04,804
[SPEAKER_20]: a

966
01:09:04,784 --> 01:09:21,655
[SPEAKER_20]: in the decisions about how we govern ourselves after next Thursday, when you've cast your vote, one of the most important questions is how do you finish the job of wiping the slate clean so that our kids and our grandkids don't continue to pay the price for our generation's debts, but you do so fairly.

967
01:09:21,895 --> 01:09:28,868
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's why I think the centre-ground position from the Liberal Democrats makes more sense than excessive cuts or excessive borrowing on either side.

968
01:09:28,848 --> 01:09:30,332
[SPEAKER_18]: Somebody's got to be Prime Minister.

969
01:09:31,535 --> 01:09:37,710
[SPEAKER_18]: Who are you going to make Prime Minister if you're in a position to decide between those two parties?

970
01:09:37,730 --> 01:09:42,662
[SPEAKER_20]: Look, here's the most unsurprising assertion of the evening.

971
01:09:42,903 --> 01:09:45,389
[SPEAKER_20]: Either David Cameron or Ed Miliband are going to be Prime Ministers.

972
01:09:45,409 --> 01:09:45,810
[SPEAKER_20]: Do you think?

973
01:09:45,790 --> 01:09:46,691
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, yes, I do.

974
01:09:46,711 --> 01:09:47,993
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, there may be no Prime Minister.

975
01:09:48,033 --> 01:09:53,480
[SPEAKER_18]: It may be so badly mashed about by the election that nobody can form a majority.

976
01:09:53,500 --> 01:09:57,666
[SPEAKER_20]: Everybody's got to behave in a grown-up, responsible way, even if they don't during the election campaign.

977
01:09:57,686 --> 01:10:01,551
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, we heard Ed Miliband here saying he wouldn't depend on the Scottish National Party.

978
01:10:01,571 --> 01:10:02,533
[SPEAKER_20]: Shall I try and answer the question?

979
01:10:02,553 --> 01:10:02,773
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes.

980
01:10:03,133 --> 01:10:06,258
[SPEAKER_20]: David Cameron or Ed Miliband are going to walk into Number 10 as Prime Minister.

981
01:10:06,718 --> 01:10:09,882
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't think that's much in doubt, and you have to decide which of those two.

982
01:10:10,383 --> 01:10:13,527
[SPEAKER_20]: The real question is, who's going to go in there alongside them?

983
01:10:13,988 --> 01:10:15,510
[SPEAKER_20]: Is it going to be Alex Salmond?

984
01:10:15,760 --> 01:10:19,304
[SPEAKER_20]: Is it going to be Nigel Farage or is it going to be me and the Liberal Democrats?

985
01:10:19,384 --> 01:10:41,025
[SPEAKER_20]: And my great fear, as I was saying earlier, is if you have David Cameron dancing to the tune of Nigel Farage, or the swivel-eyed brigade on the right wing of the Conservative Party, or you have Ed Miliband basically at the beck and call of Alex Salmond, you lurch off to the right and the left, which is not what we need as a country.

986
01:10:41,714 --> 01:10:47,972
[SPEAKER_47]: That's all well and good, but you've just told us that in 2010 you had to make a very difficult decision on tuition fees.

987
01:10:48,012 --> 01:10:53,327
[SPEAKER_47]: How do we know that you won't have to make a very difficult decision again around the things that you're promising us tonight?

988
01:10:53,487 --> 01:10:56,736
[SPEAKER_20]: That's a totally fair challenge and that's why I've been much clearer and

989
01:10:56,716 --> 01:11:04,829
[SPEAKER_20]: I hope, maybe you didn't hear it, about the red lines without which the Liberal Democrats simply won't go into any coalition government.

990
01:11:04,849 --> 01:11:06,671
[SPEAKER_20]: So, for instance, education spending.

991
01:11:06,692 --> 01:11:12,140
[SPEAKER_20]: You just heard Ed Miliband say that the Labour Party wants to increase education spending to keep up with prices.

992
01:11:12,200 --> 01:11:17,689
[SPEAKER_20]: What he didn't tell you is that there are going to be 460,000 new youngsters going into education system.

993
01:11:18,029 --> 01:11:21,154
[SPEAKER_20]: So you need to increase spending to help them as well.

994
01:11:21,134 --> 01:11:26,079
[SPEAKER_20]: The Conservatives want to do the reverse, they want to keep up with increased pupil numbers but not with prices.

995
01:11:26,499 --> 01:11:32,846
[SPEAKER_20]: Both amount to a cut, a multi-billion pound cut to the money that goes into our nurseries, our schools and our colleges.

996
01:11:33,166 --> 01:11:50,483
[SPEAKER_20]: I cannot be more clear with you, the Liberal Democrats will not go into any coalition, any government, we won't sign a coalition agreement unless, if either of those parties insist on those cuts to our education system because I think that really is short-changing the little children of today who should be given just

997
01:11:50,463 --> 01:11:54,127
[SPEAKER_18]: So you mean you want more than just a standstill?

998
01:11:54,147 --> 01:11:58,433
[SPEAKER_18]: Because you've said there are, what is it, 400,000 people coming into education?

999
01:11:58,473 --> 01:12:01,316
[SPEAKER_18]: So you want a big expansion of the education budget, not a standstill?

1000
01:12:01,336 --> 01:12:06,843
[SPEAKER_20]: I think the increase in the budget needs to keep pace not only with prices, but also with the increase of the number of children.

1001
01:12:06,863 --> 01:12:08,785
[SPEAKER_20]: Do you have any idea what the cost of that would be?

1002
01:12:08,805 --> 01:12:13,250
[SPEAKER_20]: It would be another £5 billion by the final year of the next Parliament.

1003
01:12:13,270 --> 01:12:14,031
[SPEAKER_20]: And you could find that?

1004
01:12:14,172 --> 01:12:15,273
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, you think.

1005
01:12:15,613 --> 01:12:16,234
[SPEAKER_20]: You, sir.

1006
01:12:16,889 --> 01:12:21,995
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I just wondered if you've got plans for a new job after next week when you become unemployed and your party becomes irrelevant.

1007
01:12:22,375 --> 01:12:22,715
[SPEAKER_05]: Charming.

1008
01:12:23,256 --> 01:12:23,696
[SPEAKER_18]: No, I don't.

1009
01:12:26,680 --> 01:12:27,801
[SPEAKER_18]: All right, David Jackson.

1010
01:12:27,821 --> 01:12:33,267
[SPEAKER_18]: A question from David Jackson, please.

1011
01:12:33,287 --> 01:12:44,179
[SPEAKER_06]: Nick, how do you feel about the huge increase of people driven to use food banks, many of them in work poverty or falling foul of benefit sanctions?

1012
01:12:44,497 --> 01:12:55,654
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, I think like everybody here, it's very distressing to see an increasing number of people moving to food banks and that's why every day

1013
01:12:55,769 --> 01:13:08,887
[SPEAKER_20]: that I have been in government over the last five years as we've had to clear up this unholy mess that we inherited, this massive black hole in our public finances, a broken banking system, the biggest heart attack in our economy in a generation.

1014
01:13:09,188 --> 01:13:13,994
[SPEAKER_20]: I've always tried to take decisions where we spread the burden as fairly as possible.

1015
01:13:14,295 --> 01:13:15,837
[SPEAKER_20]: So, for instance,

1016
01:13:15,817 --> 01:13:25,848
[SPEAKER_20]: have resisted, time and time again, much, much deeper cuts to benefits, to the help given to the most vulnerable, those who fall on hard times, as advocated by Conservatives in government.

1017
01:13:26,129 --> 01:13:32,416
[SPEAKER_20]: When people get back into work, particularly those on low pay, I'd be very anxious to make sure they keep more of the money they earn.

1018
01:13:32,496 --> 01:13:40,305
[SPEAKER_20]: So when I came into government, you, everybody here, all of us, would start paying income tax the moment you earned £6,400.

1019
01:13:40,285 --> 01:13:51,339
[SPEAKER_20]: on the front page of your well-thumbed copy of the 2010 Liberal Democrat manifesto, you would have seen an absolute leading commitment, which we did stick to, which was that we would raise the point at which you pay income tax.

1020
01:13:51,359 --> 01:13:54,844
[SPEAKER_20]: So you pay no income tax on the first £10,600 you earn.

1021
01:13:55,144 --> 01:14:01,793
[SPEAKER_20]: That has actually meant that 3 million people, over 3 million people, on low pay pay no income tax for the first time ever.

1022
01:14:02,213 --> 01:14:04,977
[SPEAKER_20]: The final thing I would say is about the benefit sanctions which you mentioned.

1023
01:14:04,957 --> 01:14:34,558
[SPEAKER_20]: I do, I have become persuaded, listening to the Trussell Trust and others who have provided evidence about the reasons people are using food banks, I have become persuaded that we need a, in effect, a kind of a yellow card system, that some of the sanctions that are applied to people who don't meet the conditions of their benefits shouldn't be imposed quite as harshly and automatically as they are, and that is a change that I would want to introduce in the next Parliament.

1024
01:14:35,787 --> 01:14:36,328
[SPEAKER_14]: Good evening, Nick.

1025
01:14:36,808 --> 01:14:43,195
[SPEAKER_14]: I do think you're an honourable man, but what you're forgetting is that all these sanctions were in place because you put Cameron into number 10.

1026
01:14:43,515 --> 01:14:51,703
[SPEAKER_14]: He didn't have a majority, so there'd be no work programme, nowhere near as many benefit sanctions, and you could have made a different choice, and that's why people don't trust you.

1027
01:14:51,723 --> 01:14:56,508
[SPEAKER_14]: People like me that voted for you in that election did not vote Liberal Democrat to put Cameron in number 10.

1028
01:14:56,728 --> 01:14:57,409
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah, but...

1029
01:14:57,509 --> 01:15:00,372
[SPEAKER_14]: Hang on.

1030
01:15:00,392 --> 01:15:02,034
[SPEAKER_14]: What did... Just explain, what did you expect?

1031
01:15:02,334 --> 01:15:02,975
[SPEAKER_14]: What did you want?

1032
01:15:03,695 --> 01:15:04,056
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm sorry?

1033
01:15:04,216 --> 01:15:05,237
[SPEAKER_14]: What did you want?

1034
01:15:06,567 --> 01:15:16,425
[SPEAKER_14]: My preference would have been for him to have continued negotiations with Labour, which I think a lot of Liberal Democrat natural voters are people who voted Labour that were protesting.

1035
01:15:17,046 --> 01:15:18,228
[SPEAKER_14]: But can I just make...

1036
01:15:18,248 --> 01:15:20,172
[SPEAKER_14]: There's just the little matter of democracy.

1037
01:15:20,388 --> 01:15:21,410
[SPEAKER_20]: You could have chosen.

1038
01:15:21,850 --> 01:15:22,331
[SPEAKER_20]: You did choose.

1039
01:15:22,591 --> 01:15:24,434
[SPEAKER_20]: Accept responsibility.

1040
01:15:24,514 --> 01:15:25,215
[SPEAKER_20]: You did choose.

1041
01:15:25,295 --> 01:15:26,137
[SPEAKER_20]: That was your choice.

1042
01:15:26,777 --> 01:15:27,819
[SPEAKER_20]: That's not actually the case.

1043
01:15:28,700 --> 01:15:32,826
[SPEAKER_20]: After the last election, no one won a majority, whether you all like it or not.

1044
01:15:33,027 --> 01:15:34,289
[SPEAKER_20]: The Liberal Democrats did not win.

1045
01:15:34,329 --> 01:15:35,450
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm not Prime Minister.

1046
01:15:35,550 --> 01:15:41,299
[SPEAKER_20]: I lead a party of 8% of MPs in the House of Commons, and it was the Conservatives that won the most votes and seats.

1047
01:15:41,279 --> 01:15:43,504
[SPEAKER_14]: great team and now slugging each other off.

1048
01:15:43,705 --> 01:15:46,531
[SPEAKER_20]: David Cameron says you were a great team and now you're all slugging each other off.

1049
01:15:46,952 --> 01:15:49,618
[SPEAKER_20]: He keeps talking about darkened rooms as does Ed Miliband.

1050
01:15:50,200 --> 01:15:59,541
[SPEAKER_20]: I have to say to you if either of them still think they're going to win a majority they need to go and lie down in that darkened room.

1051
01:16:00,078 --> 01:16:05,886
[SPEAKER_20]: The point I'd like to make to you and to everybody is this, is that you are the boss, right?

1052
01:16:06,146 --> 01:16:07,368
[SPEAKER_20]: We are your servants.

1053
01:16:07,708 --> 01:16:12,434
[SPEAKER_20]: You give us, through the way you vote next Thursday, our marching instructions.

1054
01:16:12,454 --> 01:16:16,239
[SPEAKER_20]: And last time, the marching instructions were very, very clear.

1055
01:16:16,520 --> 01:16:29,477
[SPEAKER_20]: The only way we could create a stable government at a time of an economic firestorm which could have engulfed this country, we could have been the next domino to fall after Greece and Portugal and Spain, was the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats.

1056
01:16:29,457 --> 01:16:31,019
[SPEAKER_14]: Greece our economy and you know it.

1057
01:16:31,039 --> 01:16:36,685
[SPEAKER_14]: Our economy was nothing like Greece's and it insults everyone's intelligence to compare the economy of this country to Greece.

1058
01:16:37,285 --> 01:16:40,869
[SPEAKER_14]: You're not that stupid.

1059
01:16:40,889 --> 01:16:41,169
[SPEAKER_20]: No, I don't.

1060
01:16:41,369 --> 01:16:46,235
[SPEAKER_20]: With the greatest respect, please don't be complacent about the state of the British economy.

1061
01:16:46,455 --> 01:16:49,498
[SPEAKER_20]: Our banking crisis was considerably worse than Greece's.

1062
01:16:49,818 --> 01:16:51,400
[SPEAKER_20]: Our deficit was just as bad.

1063
01:16:51,440 --> 01:16:52,261
[SPEAKER_20]: And so were our assets.

1064
01:16:52,541 --> 01:16:54,283
[SPEAKER_20]: If you want to see what happens

1065
01:16:54,263 --> 01:16:59,471
[SPEAKER_20]: where people don't step up to the plate, however controversial it is, to provide stable government.

1066
01:16:59,752 --> 01:17:07,384
[SPEAKER_20]: Look at the 50% youth unemployment in many other European countries where governments haven't got to grips with the economic crisis.

1067
01:17:07,464 --> 01:17:21,807
[SPEAKER_20]: I will never apologize, never apologize, whatever the short-term political effects, on the Liberal Democrats for having stepped up to the plate in a very plucky and brave way to put the country before party.

1068
01:17:27,237 --> 01:17:30,902
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't know whether the colour of your pullover is... Yellow.

1069
01:17:31,222 --> 01:17:32,304
[SPEAKER_18]: It does say something, does it?

1070
01:17:32,604 --> 01:17:32,804
[SPEAKER_18]: No.

1071
01:17:34,667 --> 01:17:35,788
[SPEAKER_45]: Your question.

1072
01:17:35,808 --> 01:17:36,750
[SPEAKER_45]: Good evening, Mr Clegg.

1073
01:17:37,331 --> 01:17:39,513
[SPEAKER_45]: You mentioned earlier about democracy.

1074
01:17:40,014 --> 01:17:49,667
[SPEAKER_45]: Do I assume from that, that when the phone rings on Friday morning, next Friday morning, that the first person you will speak to will be the person who has most seats?

1075
01:17:49,647 --> 01:18:07,564
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, I think the party that gets the biggest mandate from you, in other words the party with the most votes and the most seats, even if they haven't got a slam-dunk result, has in a democracy the result, the right, forgive me, to make, if you like the first move, to reach out to other parties to assemble a government if they so choose.

1076
01:18:07,584 --> 01:18:09,107
[SPEAKER_20]: It may not then work out.

1077
01:18:09,087 --> 01:18:14,333
[SPEAKER_20]: other parties may not reciprocate, and then other arrangements might need to be arrived at.

1078
01:18:14,353 --> 01:18:27,610
[SPEAKER_20]: But I think in a democracy it just seems to me a pretty old-fashioned principle that the party that has got its nose ahead of the other parties because of the way you vote, even if they haven't got an outright majority, has got the mandate to try and put together a government.

1079
01:18:27,710 --> 01:18:28,330
[SPEAKER_18]: All right.

1080
01:18:28,350 --> 01:18:34,538
[SPEAKER_18]: Before we go on to another question, does anybody else want to speak about food banks specifically, which was the question we had?

1081
01:18:34,518 --> 01:18:35,680
[SPEAKER_18]: And take a point, no?

1082
01:18:35,880 --> 01:18:39,246
[SPEAKER_18]: All right, let's go on to a question from Grace Davis, please.

1083
01:18:39,647 --> 01:18:40,308
[SPEAKER_18]: Grace Davis.

1084
01:18:41,029 --> 01:18:44,274
[SPEAKER_22]: Is free movement within the UK creating a problem in the EU?

1085
01:18:44,595 --> 01:18:45,797
[SPEAKER_22]: Creating a problem in the UK?

1086
01:18:45,957 --> 01:18:49,343
[SPEAKER_18]: Free movement within the EU, is it creating a problem in the UK?

1087
01:18:49,603 --> 01:18:57,196
[SPEAKER_20]: I think it did create a problem when free movement became kind of the same as the freedom to claim.

1088
01:18:57,557 --> 01:19:00,762
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't think the freedom to move is the same as the freedom to claim.

1089
01:19:00,742 --> 01:19:22,966
[SPEAKER_20]: And so, even though I am pro-European, not because I think it's perfect, but I think it makes sense for an open economy to be part of the world's largest marketplace, even though I am pro-European, I decided as Deputy Prime Minister in this coalition government to break that link so that people couldn't arrive here from elsewhere in the European Union and claim benefits, no questions asked, on the first day they arrive.

1090
01:19:23,286 --> 01:19:25,609
[SPEAKER_20]: I, by the way, would also point out it is a two-way street.

1091
01:19:25,929 --> 01:19:28,572
[SPEAKER_20]: There are roughly about as many Brits

1092
01:19:28,552 --> 01:19:33,221
[SPEAKER_20]: living and working elsewhere in the European Union than there are Europeans working in our country.

1093
01:19:33,261 --> 01:19:40,595
[SPEAKER_20]: So we kind of got to remember that it's also a freedom which many, many, many of us British people also benefit from elsewhere in Europe.

1094
01:19:41,176 --> 01:19:43,440
[SPEAKER_18]: Where do you stand on the question of a referendum?

1095
01:19:43,460 --> 01:19:44,502
[SPEAKER_18]: Because we had

1096
01:19:44,954 --> 01:19:52,388
[SPEAKER_18]: We had David Cameron saying there was no way that he'd do any kind of deal which didn't allow a referendum on Europe after the negotiations.

1097
01:19:52,408 --> 01:19:58,579
[SPEAKER_20]: So David Cameron and I, together actually in coalition government, legislated for the circumstances in which a referendum will take place.

1098
01:19:58,599 --> 01:19:59,321
[SPEAKER_20]: So you're happy with that?

1099
01:19:59,781 --> 01:20:01,485
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, I'll come to, I am happy with that.

1100
01:20:01,545 --> 01:20:02,567
[SPEAKER_20]: He appears to have changed his mind.

1101
01:20:03,168 --> 01:20:08,818
[SPEAKER_20]: I think it is perfectly sensible to say to you, in law, that in future if your powers, if the

1102
01:20:08,798 --> 01:20:12,643
[SPEAKER_20]: The sovereignty of our nation is in any way shared or pooled with the European Union.

1103
01:20:12,904 --> 01:20:16,930
[SPEAKER_20]: At that point it should be your choice whether we carry on in the European Union or not.

1104
01:20:17,250 --> 01:20:19,894
[SPEAKER_20]: It shouldn't be the choice of the Parliament or the government of the day.

1105
01:20:20,234 --> 01:20:23,779
[SPEAKER_20]: We shouldn't be able to instead give your powers away behind your back.

1106
01:20:23,799 --> 01:20:32,151
[SPEAKER_20]: That is what we legislated for in 2011 and there are stirring speeches by William Hague and David Cameron in the House of Commons saying this is the right approach.

1107
01:20:32,532 --> 01:20:33,473
[SPEAKER_20]: Within months

1108
01:20:33,453 --> 01:20:36,797
[SPEAKER_20]: The ink was barely dry on the legislation.

1109
01:20:36,817 --> 01:20:39,900
[SPEAKER_20]: The Conservatives have now changed their mind again, and again, and again, and again.

1110
01:20:39,961 --> 01:20:49,472
[SPEAKER_20]: But I remain of the view, as I always have done, is that we should have a referendum on whether we should stay in or leave the European Union when new powers are given up to the European Union.

1111
01:20:49,512 --> 01:21:00,304
[SPEAKER_20]: And I will, by the way, again, shock horror, always argue that we remain part of the European Union, flawed though it is, because I think if we quit, we become poorer, unemployment goes up, and investment in our country goes down.

1112
01:21:03,119 --> 01:21:04,558
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

1113
01:21:05,566 --> 01:21:19,983
[SPEAKER_18]: The logic of what you say, in view of what David Cameron said earlier in this programme, is that you can't go into coalition with him because you will only allow a referendum if powers are given to the European Union.

1114
01:21:20,283 --> 01:21:25,069
[SPEAKER_18]: He wants to repatriate some powers and then have a referendum and says he won't be Prime Minister if he can't.

1115
01:21:25,529 --> 01:21:27,952
[SPEAKER_20]: So he might as well say goodbye, goodbye to the coalition.

1116
01:21:27,972 --> 01:21:32,598
[SPEAKER_20]: You should have taken the opportunity when David Cameron was here to ask him about the Conservative position on Europe.

1117
01:21:32,618 --> 01:21:33,539
[SPEAKER_20]: I can only tell you about...

1118
01:21:33,559 --> 01:21:33,939
[SPEAKER_18]: He did explain it.

1119
01:21:33,959 --> 01:21:34,560
[SPEAKER_18]: No, you've probably heard it.

1120
01:21:34,540 --> 01:21:39,085
[SPEAKER_20]: The Conservatives now say they want to renegotiate but they won't tell you how they'll renegotiate.

1121
01:21:39,365 --> 01:21:41,628
[SPEAKER_20]: They float different dates about when they want to have a referendum.

1122
01:21:41,648 --> 01:21:42,349
[SPEAKER_20]: 2017?

1123
01:21:42,469 --> 01:21:49,957
[SPEAKER_20]: No, sometimes they say 2016, sometimes they say they're going to leave the European Union if they don't get what they want, sometimes they say they'll stay.

1124
01:21:50,318 --> 01:21:53,742
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know what they're going to think on Europe next Tuesday, let alone on May the 8th.

1125
01:21:54,162 --> 01:22:02,151
[SPEAKER_20]: I think there should be a referendum, I say this as a pro-European, whether we stay in or when we go out, where new powers are given up by us as a country

1126
01:22:02,131 --> 01:22:03,253
[SPEAKER_20]: to the European Union in the future.

1127
01:22:03,353 --> 01:22:04,615
[SPEAKER_18]: Only when new powers are given up.

1128
01:22:04,656 --> 01:22:07,981
[SPEAKER_18]: The man up there with spectacles, I think you've spoken already, but anyway, there we go.

1129
01:22:08,001 --> 01:22:11,027
[SPEAKER_18]: And then I'll come to you up there at the very back, under the big organ pipe.

1130
01:22:11,368 --> 01:22:12,149
[SPEAKER_31]: Yes, sir.

1131
01:22:12,169 --> 01:22:22,047
[SPEAKER_31]: We've got eight countries that are about to possibly leave the European Union, and we've got still the Eurozone crisis lying underneath.

1132
01:22:22,628 --> 01:22:23,970
[SPEAKER_31]: Eight countries about to leave?

1133
01:22:24,068 --> 01:22:26,210
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, we've got Spain, we've got Cyprus.

1134
01:22:26,351 --> 01:22:27,432
[SPEAKER_31]: They're in danger of leaving.

1135
01:22:27,492 --> 01:22:28,874
[SPEAKER_31]: There's a chance that they will leave soon.

1136
01:22:29,975 --> 01:22:37,944
[SPEAKER_31]: We've got the eurozone debt crisis still underneath the surface, and we've got 30% government bonds, European government bonds, trading at negative interest rates.

1137
01:22:38,464 --> 01:22:44,191
[SPEAKER_31]: And Germany, the heart of the EU, 70% of its government bonds are trading at negative interest rates.

1138
01:22:45,092 --> 01:22:50,278
[SPEAKER_31]: I want to know how bad does it have to get before you would think, perhaps now we should leave?

1139
01:22:50,883 --> 01:22:54,612
[SPEAKER_20]: Look, I don't, by the way, think eight countries will leave.

1140
01:22:54,773 --> 01:22:56,297
[SPEAKER_20]: It's a possibility.

1141
01:22:56,738 --> 01:22:57,881
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, everything is a possibility.

1142
01:22:57,921 --> 01:23:01,590
[SPEAKER_20]: But I absolutely don't think it's going to happen.

1143
01:23:01,630 --> 01:23:02,231
[SPEAKER_20]: I'll tell you why.

1144
01:23:02,332 --> 01:23:04,858
[SPEAKER_20]: Because in a globalized world,

1145
01:23:05,159 --> 01:23:12,574
[SPEAKER_20]: where we have big borderless threats like climate change, human traffickers and crime which cross borders.

1146
01:23:12,594 --> 01:23:17,724
[SPEAKER_20]: We have these massive corporations that sort of go from one continent to the other.

1147
01:23:17,765 --> 01:23:21,753
[SPEAKER_20]: You've got capital flows going from one corner of the planet to the next.

1148
01:23:22,053 --> 01:23:22,855
[SPEAKER_20]: It makes sense.

1149
01:23:22,995 --> 01:23:26,863
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we become stronger when we do things together.

1150
01:23:26,843 --> 01:23:33,069
[SPEAKER_20]: I just think we can fight crime, we can fight climate change, we can regulate big global corporations better when we do it together.

1151
01:23:33,129 --> 01:23:41,618
[SPEAKER_20]: By the way, it's a very similar argument to why I so passionately believe in the country, the United Kingdom, that I love so much and I don't want to see it pulled apart.

1152
01:23:41,838 --> 01:23:46,884
[SPEAKER_20]: Because I think we are just, quite simply, stronger when we do things together rather than when we fall apart.

1153
01:23:46,904 --> 01:23:50,067
[SPEAKER_31]: But it still isn't an answer to my question, which was how bad would it have to get?

1154
01:23:50,127 --> 01:23:51,248
[SPEAKER_31]: For example,

1155
01:23:51,228 --> 01:23:57,400
[SPEAKER_31]: If Greece was to leave the European Union, and then if France, which looks set to possibly vote in...

1156
01:23:57,420 --> 01:23:57,901
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't...

1157
01:23:57,921 --> 01:23:58,963
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm sorry, can I interrupt?

1158
01:23:58,984 --> 01:24:03,713
[SPEAKER_31]: France could possibly vote in the Eurosceptic National Front, and if they do, they would pull out.

1159
01:24:04,114 --> 01:24:06,619
[SPEAKER_18]: Then more and more countries... Let's not have the whole description.

1160
01:24:06,639 --> 01:24:07,721
[SPEAKER_18]: How bad does it have to get?

1161
01:24:07,861 --> 01:24:11,228
[SPEAKER_18]: Is there other circumstances in which you would say Britain

1162
01:24:11,208 --> 01:24:29,470
[SPEAKER_20]: and should be.

1163
01:24:29,450 --> 01:24:41,566
[SPEAKER_20]: Big legal firms, big aerospace firms would invest in our country if we were sort of bobbing along somewhere in the mid-Atlantic, friendless, unable to sell into our own European neighbourhood.

1164
01:24:41,586 --> 01:24:42,186
[SPEAKER_20]: Of course not.

1165
01:24:42,487 --> 01:24:43,468
[SPEAKER_20]: Jobs are at stake.

1166
01:24:43,488 --> 01:24:45,330
[SPEAKER_18]: We would still be able to sell to Europe.

1167
01:24:45,350 --> 01:24:46,312
[SPEAKER_18]: Alright, we've heard your point.

1168
01:24:46,332 --> 01:24:46,912
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you very much.

1169
01:24:46,973 --> 01:24:49,316
[SPEAKER_18]: Sorry not to keep with you, but I want to go to the man up there.

1170
01:24:49,516 --> 01:24:55,103
[SPEAKER_18]: If you believe in true democracy like you've mentioned a few times, you give the British people the say on the European Union.

1171
01:24:58,188 --> 01:25:08,048
[SPEAKER_20]: So I've explained the reasons not only when a referendum will take place, but more than that, I'm the first Deputy Prime Minister, we're the first government to ever put that into law.

1172
01:25:09,250 --> 01:25:10,793
[SPEAKER_18]: Alright, let's go on to another question.

1173
01:25:12,176 --> 01:25:13,278
[SPEAKER_18]: Brenda Hammonds, please.

1174
01:25:13,318 --> 01:25:14,340
[SPEAKER_18]: We haven't got much time left.

1175
01:25:14,380 --> 01:25:15,302
[SPEAKER_18]: Brenda Hammonds.

1176
01:25:15,856 --> 01:25:22,085
[SPEAKER_01]: With rising tension in Russia and the Middle East, will you support the need for the Trident nuclear deterrent?

1177
01:25:22,185 --> 01:25:24,348
[SPEAKER_20]: Where do you stand on the Trident nuclear deterrent?

1178
01:25:24,368 --> 01:25:36,987
[SPEAKER_20]: So I think we should keep the nuclear deterrent in this unsafe world, but I don't think we need to keep it on the same basis on which it was originally designed to flatten Moscow at the press of a button.

1179
01:25:36,967 --> 01:25:52,824
[SPEAKER_20]: and this comes down to basically whether the Trident nuclear system has four nuclear submarines or three nuclear submarines and whether you need a nuclear submarine absolutely 24 hours a day, 365 days of the whole year going around the world.

1180
01:25:52,944 --> 01:25:55,971
[SPEAKER_20]: I personally think we can step down the nuclear ladder

1181
01:25:55,951 --> 01:25:58,154
[SPEAKER_20]: while keeping ourselves safe.

1182
01:25:58,194 --> 01:26:11,332
[SPEAKER_20]: And that, I think, is a sensible, balanced way to keep ourselves safe, but not spend huge amounts of money on a Cold War replacement to the nuclear trident system, which just doesn't fit the post-Cold War world that we live in.

1183
01:26:11,372 --> 01:26:14,156
[SPEAKER_20]: The kind of threats we face, by the way, aren't like the Cold War.

1184
01:26:14,176 --> 01:26:17,120
[SPEAKER_20]: They are now stateless groups, extremist groups, terrorist groups.

1185
01:26:17,521 --> 01:26:21,507
[SPEAKER_20]: The civil war that we're seeing raging in Syria and elsewhere, those are the big threats.

1186
01:26:21,767 --> 01:26:25,452
[SPEAKER_20]: They're not solved by having four nuclear submarines rather than three.

1187
01:26:25,432 --> 01:26:26,557
[SPEAKER_20]: You sit up there at the back.

1188
01:26:26,577 --> 01:26:27,884
[SPEAKER_18]: You've spoken already, but have another go.

1189
01:26:28,567 --> 01:26:30,717
[SPEAKER_09]: You talk about keeping the country safe.

1190
01:26:31,179 --> 01:26:34,716
[SPEAKER_09]: When was this country last time attacked by another country?

1191
01:26:35,675 --> 01:26:42,983
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, we are under threat from people who don't want to attack in the conventional sense, but want to attack us, maim fellow citizens.

1192
01:26:43,003 --> 01:26:45,125
[SPEAKER_20]: It's because we're meddling in their countries.

1193
01:26:45,145 --> 01:26:57,078
[SPEAKER_20]: Can I... Well, I don't actually think there's any excuse that any rational or reasonable person can give to those people who want to kill innocent British citizens through terrorist acts in our cities.

1194
01:26:58,740 --> 01:27:02,003
[SPEAKER_20]: And whilst... Whilst...

1195
01:27:03,383 --> 01:27:14,534
[SPEAKER_20]: Whilst as a good old-fashioned liberal, I'm the first person to defend our civil liberties and our freedoms, I think there is no inconsistency between defending our freedoms and keeping ourselves safe.

1196
01:27:14,854 --> 01:27:20,380
[SPEAKER_20]: We don't make ourselves any less free by making ourselves any less safe.

1197
01:27:20,460 --> 01:27:21,781
[SPEAKER_18]: One last thing, if I could ask you this.

1198
01:27:21,801 --> 01:27:27,106
[SPEAKER_18]: You've said you want the Liberal Democrats to be the heart for the Conservatives, the brains for Labour.

1199
01:27:27,446 --> 01:27:32,091
[SPEAKER_18]: If neither of those works and you can't form a coalition, would you remain leader of the Liberal Democrats?

1200
01:27:32,071 --> 01:27:34,295
[SPEAKER_18]: or would you see your job as over?

1201
01:27:34,816 --> 01:27:35,517
[SPEAKER_20]: Look, I want to carry on.

1202
01:27:35,537 --> 01:27:36,719
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm 48 years old.

1203
01:27:36,739 --> 01:27:37,660
[SPEAKER_20]: I've got bags of energy.

1204
01:27:38,281 --> 01:27:46,215
[SPEAKER_20]: I believe in what the Liberal Democrats stand for, which is to strike the right balance between creating a strong economy but doing so fairly.

1205
01:27:46,235 --> 01:27:49,861
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't think that's represented on either the right or the left of British politics.

1206
01:27:49,881 --> 01:27:51,985
[SPEAKER_20]: But look, no, I have to stop you there.

1207
01:27:52,465 --> 01:27:53,607
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you very much indeed.

1208
01:27:54,208 --> 01:27:55,390
[SPEAKER_18]: A nice, brief answer.

1209
01:27:55,450 --> 01:27:55,851
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

1210
01:28:03,847 --> 01:28:10,939
[SPEAKER_18]: Sorry to cut Mr. Clake short, but we do have to stop because we have exactly 90 minutes for this program.

1211
01:28:10,959 --> 01:28:14,365
[SPEAKER_18]: That ends, incidentally, of course, as you would guess, this edition of Question Time.

1212
01:28:14,385 --> 01:28:23,159
[SPEAKER_18]: We're going to be back, not next Thursday when we have the election results, but on Friday evening at 9 o'clock when we'll be looking back at the election and seeing what's happened, a first chance to talk about it.

1213
01:28:23,760 --> 01:28:28,649
[SPEAKER_18]: So from here, my thanks, of course, to our party leaders and particularly to all of you who came to take part in it in Leeds.

1214
01:28:29,009 --> 01:28:29,550
[SPEAKER_18]: Good night.

1215
01:28:39,301 --> 01:28:41,206
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, we've covered him next on BBC1.

1216
01:28:41,386 --> 01:28:45,717
[SPEAKER_04]: And what exactly has Kayleigh been doing with Ken, her 80-year-old labour?

1217
01:28:46,358 --> 01:28:47,301
[SPEAKER_04]: John can't believe it.

1218
01:28:47,481 --> 01:28:59,892
[SPEAKER_04]: It's Peter Kay's Car Share.

